commit_message:
Add xml support to the floating ip and router

Creating xml version for the neutron router and floatingip related
operation. The test_floating_ips.py also extended with the XML variant.

Change-Id: I5e85cd263828a127ed48db04b19fbf4d145f1d87

commit_message:
Clean up existing instances when not using tenant isolation

The test_list_servers_negative tests require that there are no existing
instances in the database when they run and will fail if any are found
under the primary/alternate user/tenant.

When running tempest with allow_tenant_isolation=false on a slower
system, there is a race where instances from previous tests are still
cleaning up in the background and cause test_list_servers_negative to
fail in setup.

This patch makes test_list_servers_negative block while the deleted
instances are being cleaned up in the background if running without
tenant isolation.

Closes-Bug: #1234370

Change-Id: I8519cba1fcf6ff39d69839783d07359544509db5

commit_message:
feat: add logging to proxy

Adds reasonable logging to the proxy, especially at the transport
layer and for cache debugging.

Mostly imitates the logging style used by the queues server.

Partially-Implements blueprint placement-service
Change-Id: If5490a3b18bf660e9c7a57f47959eedacc936b48
Closes-Bug: 1230379

Change-Id: I9113f4b4e4b02de62b7470d3dca4d08fdd0769cc

commit_message:
Open 1.3.x development

Add a "pre version" to setup.cfg so pbr will generate version numbers
on a different version series from stable/havana. We can remove this
again after we tag the first alpha of 1.3.0.

Change-Id: I4cea570273debc614d8fdd904d66a4d76a2fb4bb

'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2013-10-03 21:57:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

So I was thinking about this more and I am wondering if we should start making the task names the following (which I think we talked about before).

Instead of the task name just being a single string what about the following idea.

Task_name would move from 'name' to be a tuple of (name, uuid), the name would be the existing name in combination with a uuid, for storage and persistence we would store that tuple, and for migration and reconstruction we would only use the first element (the name). That way instances of tasks can be duplicated in a flow (since the tuple of (name, uuid) would be unique) and also we can locate all the tasks still by name if we want."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2013-10-04 06:43:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

commit_message:
Check for duplicate task names on flattening

Task names should be unique within flow. But complete set of tasks
is not generally known until flow flattening is run. So, we check
task names uniqueness as soon as we have execution graph.

Change-Id: I658b3ae606fc79e600d90b51f0b4ed4f4e7d511d

Correctly save task versions

When task is added to storage or task detail is saved to persistence
backend, task version should be saved with it.

commit_message:
xenapi: refactor: move RawTGZImage to common

During the review of https://review.openstack.org/40909 it was
requested, that the RawTGZImage class should be moved to a common
territory, so that others can re-use it later.

Fixes bug 1220596

unbroke stable gate (chown)

This change ensures the directory is created, even if it is not used by all
all branches.

commit_message:
Wrapping and serializing failures

* save task failures to sqlalchemy backend and restore them
  from there;
* for any wrapped exception use common WrappedFailre exception
  type, which makes it easier to handle particular exception types;
* several minor improvements.

Affects-db: this change adds db migration that looses exception
    information for saved task details.
Change-Id: I575282002e6999646bbf51f492b82a7e3525787a

cloud-init has been ported to numerous distros

http://community.linuxmint.com/software/view/cloud-init

commit_message:
Split setup-passwords into undercloud and overcloud

Don't assume overcloud and undercloud can access the same file to get
the passwords from. Split up setup-passwords so
setup-undercloud-passwords is used in devtest_undercloud and
setup-overcloud-passwords is used in devtest_overcloud.

Change-Id: I47de68d081ab3d8e83d014d416e229c055b42ec8

commit_message:
Fix l2 pop doesn't propagate ip address updates

Propagates ip address changes when an ip address is :
added, removed, or changed.
Add a new rpc call for the updates of forwarding informations.

Fixes: Bug #1234137
Change-Id: Ib5b971bd02f20a0ea73f88ce9685e944226bb5a2

commit_message:
Fix the log format of obj_load_attr()

The log of nova-compute is filled with the following traceback
due to invalid log format.

Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/logging/__init__.py", line 846, in emit
    msg = self.format(record)
  File "/opt/stack/nova/nova/openstack/common/log.py", line 553, in format
    return logging.StreamHandler.format(self, record)
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/logging/__init__.py", line 723, in format
    return fmt.format(record)
  File "/opt/stack/nova/nova/openstack/common/log.py", line 517, in format
    return logging.Formatter.format(self, record)
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/logging/__init__.py", line 464, in format
    record.message = record.getMessage()
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/logging/__init__.py", line 328, in getMessage
    msg = msg % self.args
TypeError: %u format: a number is required, not str
Logged from file instance.py, line 479

This patch fixes the problem.

Fixes bug #1231816

Change-Id: I88892ac70c78eab98f6eaa406ceef101543d7358

commit_message:
Allow service_id per service_type for Usage Events

    notification_service_id is not of type DictOpt,
    this allows for a comma-sep list of
    service_type:service_id pairs

commit_message:
Arista ML2 mechanism driver clean up and integration with port binding

fixes bug: 1215097

This patch addresses minor cleanups and integration with port binding
and dhcp support into Arista ML2 mechanism driver.

Allow early host % on validate

it doesn't get's default value.

commit_message:
Catch volume errors during local delete

The delete code in compute/manager.py has a catch-all exception
handler for any volume related errors that occur during deletion.
This change brings the local_delete() method in compute/api.py
in line with that.

Fixes bug: 1224546

Change-Id: I399075f29d202355b28e7da1b2f1a29a66c86a4e

commit_message:
Fixing decorators for rally.benchmark.base.Scenario

This patch fixes a couple of decorators for the base scenario class from
@staticmethod to @classmethod so that one can use the openstack clients
defined in class_init() from those decorated methods.

Closes-Bug: #1234961
Blueprint test-engine-remove-pytest

Change-Id: I239c2df06412f840aab325be3529c04ade13529b

commit_message:
Move rally.task to rally.db.task

Actually task module is used to simplify work with rally.db.api

So it should be in rally.db not on global level

Change-Id: I780db5f4fe8cdcd6b2f554ed3f5668dbb993e0fe

I'm a bit leery of making Oracle/DB2 style "LIKE %foo%" checking the default for databases other than mysql/postgres/sqlite, because I don't know that all other databases support it. commit_message:
Code change for regex filter matching

Remove REGEXP_LIKE operator for oracle db backend since it's not suitable,
Such as:
Oracle: 'select xxx from xxx where REGEXP_LIKE (column, pattern)'
Mysql: 'select xxx from xxx where column REGEXP pattern'

For the simple pattern matching(LIKE operator) used for unsupported backend db,
add '%' wildcard character on both sides of the value.

Change-Id: I4682d38086a06032bb5650a14b253f6b2b859613
Closes-Bug: #1230102

commit_message:
VMware: Check for the propSet attribute's existence before using

There may be cases when the call to RetrievePropertiesEx may have missing
data. That is, the propSet field may be missing. In this case the missing
field will be logged. This will help with troubleshooting the problem.

Fields may be missing due to one of the following reasons:
 - SystemError if there was some unknown problem reading the value
 - NoPermission if the logged in session did not have permission to read
   the value

The propSet attribute is marked as optional in the API documentation so this
should have been anticipated and this can be interpreted as a bug in the
client code.

http://pubs.vmware.com/vsphere-51/index.jsp#com.vmware.wssdk.apiref.doc/vmodl.query.PropertyCollector.ObjectContent.html

Fixes bug: 1215958

Change-Id: If8fd912327e057320cd6013c276000617b9c320c

commit_message:
plug_vif raise NotImplementedError instead of pass

The Hyper-V, VMware, Docker and PowerVM drivers raise
NotImplementedError from the plug_vifs and unplug_vifs
methods rather than pass.
The compute manager handles the NotImplementedError
case when initializing the host.

Fixed bug 1218593

Change-Id: Id17a1f691f46816eadfe257d9ac0cc46502318ef

commit_message:
fix: do not duplicate queues across partitions

This patch fixes a proxy bug that allows queues to be duplicated
across partitions. This happens because the catalogue isn't checked
for project/queue existence before forwarding requests to a marconi
partition.

Caching is also added to queue on_put to quickly determine if a
particular project/queue exists.

A unit test suite is added that verifies that this has been fixed, as
well as checking various properties on the queue resource.

Closes-Bug: 1234849
Partially-Implements blueprint placement-service

Change-Id: I2e8ca29abd58ecb6f33f0f296119e341504ea3fd

commit_message:
Addition of mechanism to opt-out from catalog data during token validation

The additional query parameter: nocatalog in GET /v3/auth/tokens allows
the requestor to receive a token response omitting the catalog data.
This makes the token response sensibly smaller.

Token validation Catalog opt-out example:
GET /v3/auth/token?nocatalog

blueprint token-valid-catalog-opt-out

Change-Id: I722893ea7237530731f22f9cae643fa2adea5833

commit_message:
Use load-image -d in overcloud for now.

To facilitate CD of the overcloud use the -d flag in load-images.

Change-Id: Icea39faf1cab513700c234ebc3257e9d3edd2cc1

commit_message:
Fixes the usage of PowerVMFileTransferFailed class

If it fails in the process of "Calculate file size in multiples of 512
bytes", the exception.PowerVMFileTransferFailed message is illegal.
"KeyError: u'file_path'" is occurs when there is no argument.

Change-Id: I15a7467bbc103f683d82949dc0892210cd63c4b6
Closes-Bug: #1223198

commit_message:
Fix races in cells extension tests

A global was used for a cell list and tests would update this global and
fail depending on order run, etc.

Fixes bug 1235399

Change-Id: Ib06cfc89076e87ac3cfedd796687059862f20406

subject: Document the joy of bringing up a real undercloud.
messages:

- gate-tripleo-incubator-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/96/49296/1/check/gate-tripleo-incubator-docs/488f01d/doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 13m 08s
'}, {'account_id': 6449, 'date': '2013-10-02 08:20:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(6 inline comments)

That is one heck of a lot of joy right there :O

Few nitpicks in the presentation, but nothing really in the content (I suspect this deployment guide will confuse a lot of people, but IMHO that is better solved with tooling and install helpers, than more verbose docs)"}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-10-02 10:12:22.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-10-02 10:13:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thanks Chris, actioned. And yes, we dont' want better docs, we want better software. This essentially provides a hitlist of things to fix; some of which will apply to the overcloud and thus be high priority, and some less so."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-02 10:43:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

Build succeeded.

- gate-tripleo-incubator-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/96/49296/2/check/gate-tripleo-incubator-docs/3b0597f/doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 1m 12s
'}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2013-10-02 20:51:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(5 inline comments)

Definitely a lot of good useful info here.  However, I'm not sure it's in the best consumable format for docs.  It reads more like notes, then an actual way to deploy something.

Granted, the other HOWTO's on the deploying page leave quite a bit left up to the user to figure out.  And in fact, I'd say this patch provides *too* much info compared to what else is on the deploying page.

Maybe just add a higher level HOWTO to deploying, and add a new docs page for this particular setup with the concrete examples and commands.

Regardless, I have a few specific comments inline that I think need looking at."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-10-02 21:10:23.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-02 21:11:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me

Build succeeded.

- gate-tripleo-incubator-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/96/49296/3/check/gate-tripleo-incubator-docs/283dac7/doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 24s
'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-10-02 21:27:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: (5 inline comments)

@James thanks for the improvements. I agree this isn't brilliant, however it's a trade off: this is important info we need captured somewhere. But we actually want this to be code, not docs. But this is undercloud and with the new CD approach which seems to have had favourable feedback, we should be focusing our efforts on delivering the CD overcloud, so this stuff is all back-burner, except where it also affects the overcloud deployments (which some of it will). So I want to minimise the polish we put on this information - just enough to enable folk following in footsteps - or working on the CD cloud - to benefit, but not polishing it by adding things we'll just turn into automation in the near future."}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2013-10-02 21:51:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

That's fair.  I understand the desire to not spend time polishing.  But, now that we're on docs.openstack.org, I could see newcomers expecting more, or just being downright confused by what they're reading there. 

Given it's purpose, I think it would be better served as documentation for the CD environment. With perhaps a link on the deploying page pointing it out as a way to setup the undercloud on baremetal."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-10-02 22:57:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I see your point, but actually Deploying.rst was intended originally to describe how to deploy; the lack of detail was due to our lack of capability at the time. Is there anything cheap we can do to mitigate confusion?

Or perhaps: lets put this up and if there is confusion, I commit to doing another patch to really make things clearer.'}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-10-03 16:15:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

To add support to Robert's position, incubator is where things go when it isn't clear what the next step is.

I think that much of this will land in an official OpenStack deployment guide, and some of what we have will go directly from incubator into it.

Unfortunately, for now, this is the imperfect hunk of marble with a basic human shape carved out.. it will take a while to chip away everything and reveal the masterpiece. ;)"}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2013-10-04 11:36:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

commit_message:
Use mock to do unit tests for pxe driver

OpenStack is moving to use mock instead of mox for unit tests
in order to be ready for python 3. This patch changes the
test cases for pxe driver from using mox to mock.

Change-Id: I96eb9de4cd7c93619c71840b4ce79d5b83f832e6
Closes-Bug: 1229398

commit_message:
Make unstack.sh work when run as root

Make unstack.sh check whether it's running as root, and if so, use the
same approach as stack.sh in order to switch to the $STACK_USER account,
and re-exec itself.  In contrast to stack.sh, we can skip the sudo and
$STACK_USER account setup code, because this should have already been
taken care of via a stack.sh run (and if it hasn't, presumably there is
nothing worth "unstacking").

Change-Id: If42ad6270d60f4b01b1587032448654699d4c812

I don't think we really want to be supporting running stack.sh as root"}, {'account_id': 2394, 'date': '2013-10-04 13:18:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

We are *already* supporting running stack.sh as root.  This merely fixes it.'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2013-10-04 16:10:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'd argue that we _don't_ support running as root but we have an ugly hack to let people start stack.sh as root.  This has actually caused more problems than I think is worth.  If FORCE needs to be passed, what about HTTP_PROXY?  Or any of the other things that probably needs to be in localrc anyway?

I'd like to dump the whole root hack thing..."}, {'account_id': 2394, 'date': '2013-10-04 17:04:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

There's nothing on the website or in the README.md which says stack.sh should or shouldn't be run as root.  stack.sh's current behaviour is to fairly gracefully handle running as root, so it seems entirely reasonable for newcomers to assume it should work.  If it really is officially unsupported, then it's a very misleading state of affairs for newcomers :-/  In that case it should at very least barf with a "please don't run me as root" error message.

I totally share your concerns about HTTP_PROXY etc. so I'm not going to argue against the idea of removing root support in either the short or long term.  However I think we need to clarify the status quo and set users' expectations correctly ASAP.

So IMHO there are only three reasonable ways forward:

1. *immediately* remove support for running as root, and update the website to explain how to correctly set up sudoers, or

2. accept short-term fixes for current breakage when running as root, but maintain a medium or long term target of removing support for running as root, or

3. decide to maintain support for running as root indefinitely.

What I'd hate to see happen is:

4. my fixes for the breakage get rejected, but partially broken root support is left in for any significant period of time.

On a similar topic, it's not very clear from the website (to me at least) which distro platforms are supported or where support can be found, but that's another can of worms which I'll open elsewhere ...'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2013-10-04 18:06:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

You are correct about the perils of leaving partially broken code in place, and since I've considered this bit broken since it was added here is my proposal: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/49798/"}, {'account_id': 2394, 'date': '2013-10-04 20:09:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

Superceded by 49798.'}]

commit_message:
Pass FORCE through to sudo invocation

If we ran stack.sh as root, pass through the value of the FORCE variable
through to the child stack.sh running as the 'stack' user via sudo,
otherwise the child process will not have FORCE set and will abort
prematurely.

Change-Id: I54018fc478728b6246921746ef82d893bbcd0dab

commit_message:
py33: sort hosts while treeize AvailabilityZone

In Python 3.3, hash randomization is enabled by default. It causes the
iteration order of dicts and sets to be unpredictable and differ across
Python runs.

sort the hosts while treeize AvailabiltyZone.

Test cmd
--------
for i in {1..100}; do echo $i; \
tox -e py33 |grep test_detail_availability_zone; done

Change-Id: I9ab25ef52d6d19b45a39f04cbcde864ee225b4cc
Close-Bug: #1235067

commit_message:
py33: unify the input of request to json format

In novaclient.client.HTTPClient.request, json.dumps() process the
body of "POST":
kwargs['data'] = json.dumps(kwargs['body'])

So, in test case, we should pass the same forat for mock.call().

Also, transform the "data" variable to json format.

Close-Bug #1234067

Change-Id: I3a0abaa8064b4360cb94b7b205454e26bddef8e4

commit_message:
py33: align the order of parameters for urlencode()

In Python 3.3, hash randomization is enabled by default. It causes the
iteration order of dicts and sets to be unpredictable and differ across
Python runs.

In the test case, the fixed expecting string will not match the test
result, it is relying on the dict order.

This change transforms the input dict to a sequence of two-element list,
with fixed order, and update the related expecitng string in test case.

Close-Bug #1234438

Change-Id: Ic7846279a9f508a856cd4ee70408d537088792f2

Python 2:
str.encode = encode(...)
    S.encode([encoding[,errors]]) -> object

Python 3:

    S.encode(encoding='utf-8', errors='strict') -> bytes

In Python 3, strings are always Unicode. There is no need to encode.

commit_message:
py33: safe_encode() returns bytes in Python 3

Python 2:
str.encode = encode(...)
    S.encode([encoding[,errors]]) -> object

Python 3:
str.encode = encode(...)
    S.encode(encoding='utf-8', errors='strict') -> bytes

In Python 3, strings are always Unicode.  safe_encode() returns
"bytes", the "\n" will be printed literally, it is not expected.

bytes.decode() will transform bytes to str, which will be printed
properly.

Close-bug: #1229150
Change-Id: If926d3f7837673b4608ae667d34cea3c78e82e5d

commit_message:
Clarify what overcloud is controlling in devtest.

KVM was specified as what overcloud controls, but this can actually
be a variety of virtualization options, including QEMU (as used in
testing) and Xen.

This hopefully clarifies that the documentation refers to what the
overcloud controls, not what it is.

Change-Id: Ib83a135f1a2376207ad5aafe96ae33584f52ae8d

commit_message:
chore: Rename MONGODB_TEST_LIVE to MARCONI_TEST_MONGODB

This patch renames the MONGODB_TEST_LIVE environment variable so that it
is consistent with MARCONI_TEST_SLOW. Testing for the renamed variable
was also DRY'd up using a decorator.

Change-Id: I6b08ae2ca2f86daf50df11219cc8c0a465e86c13

commit_message:
Using no proxy option to skip wget and curl proxy settings in config

When end users specify proxy settings in config file for wget /etc/wgetrc:
http_proxy = http://...
or for curl ${HOME}/.curlrc:
proxy = http://...

Using `http_proxy="" wget' can not skip the proxy setting in the
config files, also it can skip proxy settings in env viriables.

In order to skip proxy setting in both env and config file, we pass
--no-proxy option for wget, and --noproxy '*' for curl.

Fixes bug #1224836

Change-Id: I2b25aeca9edf2ce4525fb1db325e5e24c18b4d55

[{'created': '2013-10-01 16:56:38.000000000', 'message': "set errexit and xtrace in helper scripts

stack.sh invokes some helper scripts as separate processes, rather than
by source'ing them.  As with stack.sh itself, abort immediately on the
first error, so that errors don't compound and result in confusing error
messages.  If one of these helper scripts aborts, stack.sh itself will
also abort in the usual manner.

Due to the change in behaviour, tweak some mv invocations to ensure that
they don't trigger false failures.

As with stack.sh itself, also enable xtrace so we can see exactly what's
happening.  In particular this allows us to see the cause of any

enabled.

Change-Id: I7a55784c31e5395e29ab9bbe2bb112b83b9be693
"}]
commit_message:
set errexit and xtrace in helper scripts

stack.sh invokes some helper scripts as separate processes, rather than
by source'ing them.  As with stack.sh itself, abort immediately on the
first error, so that errors don't compound and result in confusing error
messages.  If one of these helper scripts aborts, stack.sh itself will
also abort in the usual manner.

Due to the change in behaviour, tweak some mv invocations to ensure that
they don't trigger false failures.

As with stack.sh itself, also enable xtrace so we can see exactly what's
happening.  In particular this allows us to see the cause of any
premature termination due to a command failing whilst errexit is
enabled.

Change-Id: I7a55784c31e5395e29ab9bbe2bb112b83b9be693

commit_message:
Remove trove as default value for Service Name

* This causes service catalog lookup issues when the Catalog
  contains service_type = database, but service_name = somethine_else

fixes bug 1228372

Change-Id: I1f7eebb06d7f57c0ecc95d8c05104f43e803c406

'}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2013-10-02 16:52:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

I gave this patch a very quick read, and do not see any obvious problems with the implementation. It looks very good, and I'm giving it a +1 (for now). But I'm wondering whether this is the best (or even correct) approach to solving the problem of rejecting status updates from recently unbound L2 agents. 

First, rather than adding the host param to the RPC method signatures, couldn't the agent_id be looked up in the agents_db to obtain the host (if that's what's needed)?

Second, for the ML2 plugin implementation, it seems the currently bound mechanism driver should be involved in deciding whether the update should be accepted or rejected. This way, we'd be verifying not just that the host is the same, but that any other details the mechanism driver cares about are the same. If we were ever trying to run multiple L2 agents on the same host, this would seem to be needed.

Anyway, I'm not necessarily opposed to this current implementation going in (after closer review), but wanted to raise the possibilities of addressing this without modifying the RPC interface, and of involving the ML2 mechanism driver. Any other opinions on this?"}, {'account_id': 2888, 'date': '2013-10-03 08:02:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

thanks for the review bob,

my first intention was to use the agent_id sent by the agent, but it is totally different from the one stored in the DB. May be the good code would have been to refactor this part, so that the agent_id would be sent by the plugin, but it was more disruptive. 

I totally agree that the mechanism drivers should be involved during the migration, through the port_update, but this should be handle in a negotiation between nova and neutron, to know if the mechanism driver accepts the new binding proposed by nova. This part could be handled by the scheduler.'}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2013-10-03 16:01:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

I think this approach is ok and addresses a bug which people will hit when using ML2, so I'm inclined to approve this one."}, {'account_id': 7141, 'date': '2013-10-04 14:41:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 6524, 'date': '2013-10-04 15:17:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Are you sure that neutron.plugins.brocade.NeutronPlugin.BridgeRpcCallbacks.update_device_down() doesn't need to do the host check?"}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2013-10-04 18:20:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Looks good to me (core reviewer); Approved

Agreed this is sufficient for now, and involving mechanism drivers can be considered in icehouse. The brocade plugin can be addressed via a follow-up patch if needed.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-04 18:20:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: No score

commit_message:
change port status only if port is bound to the good host

if host is set in the rpc message update_device_up/down sent by the agent,
the port status will be changed only if the port is bound to the host.

Change-Id: I0e607c734fbebf0b69f83c3bbd3e25a9783672dc
Closes-Bug: #1224967

commit_message:
Remove cruft from setup.cfg

packages is recursive, so there is no need to list subpackages
versions are set by tags, so the version in the file is not needed
non-d2to1-based pbr does not need the hook specification

Change-Id: Id5e6c19dfe81c630862e9b87b7f9e5f67a965945

openSUSE's python-virtualenv rpm depends on the python-pip rpm, but
tools/install_pip.sh prefers to deinstall the latter (if installed) and
install pip directly from upstream source instead.

commit_message:
Fix handling of pip and virtualenv on openSUSE

openSUSE's python-virtualenv rpm depends on the python-pip rpm, but
tools/install_pip.sh prefers to deinstall the latter (if installed) and
install pip directly from upstream source instead.

This deinstallation of python-pip will break if attempted via rpm -e,
since rpm does not transitively remove dependents (in this case
python-virtualenv).  In contrast, "zypper rm" does, so we switch to
that.

It is safe to remove the python-virtualenv package, since stack.sh will
install virtualenv via pip instead.

Change-Id: I5bc23de0f2de2e3940c4be3b76b7c0634836239b

commit_message:
Changes Exception to Log Message

The optional information being set by the metaquery object is not
implemented when using a SQL alchemy backend. Presenly, the raised
exception causes ceilometer to stop and abandon reporting. This
workaround will allow for functionality and will log that metaquery
is not implemeted.

This has been applied to Metering, Resources, and Sample.

The log level has been set to "warn" and the loop will allow the
user to know what the "metaquery" was and that it is not implemented
at this time.

- update : fixed typo.

Change-Id: Ic4d6a993f856d361e4c244167000eb0caa790086
Closes-Bug: #1093625

commit_message:
Fix the wrong params of attach/detach interface for compute driver

The reason of attach_interface failed is current code passing VIF object
to attach_interface, but it expected NetworkInfo object. And as the
comment of attach/detach_interface, they should only accept one
interface to instance. So correct the interface signature only accept
an VIF object. And correct the fake driver behavior, make the test running
correctly.

Change-Id: Id0d28c39fb543853bd710fcb3c3b611306b4fb8f
Close-bug: #1233504

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-27 14:38:59.000000000', 'message': "Resource limits check sometimes enforced for forced scheduling

Resource limit checks on a compute manager are based on the
contents of filter_properites['limits'].   This in turn is
populated by the scheduler after the host has been selected by
scheduler.utils.populate_filter_properties.   The limits value
is taken from the host_state, which is maintained as a local data
in the host manager. The host_state limits values are populated
by the various filters, for example the ram filter sets
limits['memory_mb'] based on its configuration.

In the case of scheduling to a forced host the filters are
bypassed, so the contents of the host_state['limits'] value
depends on whether the scheduler has already placed a non-forced
instance onto that host (and thus run the filters to populate the
limits).   If it has then the compute manager will impose the
limits, if it hasn't then the limits will be empty and there will
be no check.

As forcing bypasses the filters and is a privileged operation the
limits should always be cleared in the filter_properties in this
case to avoid the limit check on the compute manager.

Fixed bug: 1231963

commit_message:
Resource limits check sometimes enforced for forced scheduling

Resource limit checks on a compute manager are based on the
contents of filter_properites['limits'].   This in turn is
populated by the scheduler after the host has been selected by
scheduler.utils.populate_filter_properties.   The limits value
is taken from the host_state, which is maintained as a local data
in the host manager. The host_state limits values are populated
by the various filters, for example the ram filter sets
limits['memory_mb'] based on its configuration.

In the case of scheduling to a forced host the filters are
bypassed, so the contents of the host_state['limits'] value
depends on whether the scheduler has already placed a non-forced
instance onto that host (and thus run the filters to populate the
limits).   If it has then the compute manager will impose the
limits, if it hasn't then the limits will be empty and there will
be no check.

As forcing bypasses the filters and is a privileged operation the
limits should always be cleared in the filter_properties in this
case to avoid the limit check on the compute manager.

Fixed bug: 1231963

Change-Id: Ic7ff5d1fc652a8bdf6a0cf8e6ef063d9f2e7ab16

commit_message:
Make LiveMigrateTask use build_request_spec()

Some filters like TrustedFilter makes use of extra_specs. Currently,
when live-migration uses the scheduler to select a host, it constructs
a request_spec that has no extra_specs in it.

By making use of the existing helper method build_request_spec(), the
request to the scheduler will include extra_specs.

Change-Id: I5bc6c6418653c256a42da7b0a343086ec9863da1
Closes-Bug: #1224014

commit_message:
Ensure image property not set to None in build_request_spec()

This is in preparation for having scheduler.util.build_request_spec()
construct the request_spec in the live migration code. Specifically, this
change is needed to avoid reintroducing bug #1199811.

Change-Id: I0cc6b6ec7be7a0afbe184b208f2e16fd5cd4452c
Related-Bug: #1224014

commit_message:
Fix type is overwritten when UPDATE cell without type specified

If you not specified the 'cell-type' in UPDATE request,
  the value will be overwritten by the default value, 'child'.
That's not correct, you need to reserve the existing cell-type.

The issue is also involved in the new V3-api.

Fixes bug: 1224461

Change-Id: I5c5043b9e5e0c33995422094284c3f19aac78593

commit_message:
Add third element to RPC versions for backports

This makes the RPC version support three elements, adding a "revision"
in addition to the major and minor version. The revision would always
be zero for the master branch of a service, but could be incremented
for stable versions. This provides us some room to backport fixes
that affect RPC versions in such a way that would avoid breaking
the version lineage for systems running stable versions that may
some day be involved in a rolling upgrade to a version from master.

I didn't find any tests for version_is_compatible(), so I added
some for existing version scenarios, as well as new ones with
revisions. They also serve to validate that this doesn't break
anything for code using two-element versions (the expectation is that
two-element versions will still be used everywhere until a third
is needed).

Change-Id: I239c17a3e305f572493498c4b96ee3c7514c5881

subject: Adds note about block size settings to accomodate custom block sizes
messages:
[{'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-24 18:18:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Works for me

Build succeeded.

- gate-openstack-manuals-validate http://logs.openstack.org/12/48112/1/check/gate-openstack-manuals-validate/3aefe86 : SUCCESS in 4m 17s
'}, {'account_id': 321, 'date': '2013-09-26 00:57:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I'm having some trouble understanding this functionality.

(Added Chet Burgess to this review, the questions are directed at him

How does an operator set the block size for a particular backend? Is it by a config option in cinder.conf? Even looking at the code, I couldn't figure this out. I assume this is per backend and not per volume?

The original commit message says "Sometimes we need to set a specific block size or operations against the backend will result in I/O errors". Can you give an example of when this would happen? In particular, which backends need this to function correctly?


Also:

* the original DocImpact mentioned needing libvirt 0.10.2 or greater for this functionality, that's missing from the doc patch.

* The original commit log also mentioned that changing the block size can be used to tune performance, I think that should be mentioned in the docs as another use case for this option.'}, {'account_id': 3189, 'date': '2013-09-26 05:39:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Lorin,

I've added John Griffith to add some insight as well since he was the original reporter of the issue in nova, and primarily did the work on the cinder side to support this feature. The nova bug should arguably have been a blueprint since it was a request to support a new feature in cinder.

Towards your specific questions:

> How does an operator set the block size for a particular backend? Is it by a config option in cinder.conf? Even looking at the code, I couldn't figure this out. I assume this is per backend and not per volume?

This is actually cinder volume driver specific. If the cinder volume driver requires connections from VMs to use a specific block size it sets this in the connection_info that is based to nova. I'm not entirely sure how each cinder volume driver handles this. In the SolidFire case I believe the driver detects the hardware version of the storage array and tunes the block sizes accordingly. As such its not something the operator can control. John, can you comment?

>The original commit message says "Sometimes we need to set a specific block size or operations against the backend will result in I/O errors". Can you give an example of when this would happen? In particular, which backends need this to function correctly?

Again this is cinder volume driver specific. I believe that SolidFire has an example of a class of hardware that needs a specific block size. I'm not extremely familiar with cinder so this is a question that is probably best answered by the cinder team or John who implemented the feature on the cinder side. nova is simply acting on the data provided by cinder.

>the original DocImpact mentioned needing libvirt 0.10.2 or greater for this functionality, that's missing from the doc patch.

This was the primary reason for the DocImpact. Officially nova requires libvirt 0.9.6 or later. Unfortunately the ability to set block sizes is not available until 0.10.2. The requirements from the cinder team was that any block size passed via connection_info should be considered mandatory. If we see a block size passed during the attach_volume call we check the libvirt version. If the version is too old we will throw and Invalid exception and the attach will fail. We will log a line like the following:

"Volume sets block size, but libvirt '0.10.2 or later is required."

As such I felt it was important to note to users that some cinder volume drivers will require a newer version of libvirt in order for volumes to be used with VMs.

> The original commit log also mentioned that changing the block size can be used to tune performance, I think that should be mentioned in the docs as another use case for this option.

This was more of an observation. Again its up to the specific cinder volume drivers to expose (or not) a mechanism to do this. Some drivers may not expose a mechanism in which case the tuning is somewhat irrelevant from the operators perspective as the driver should simply "do the right thing".

There should probably be a corresponding document written and/or referenced that documents which cinder volume drivers pass block size info as well as how to tune these values (if possible) on the cinder side.'}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2013-10-01 22:03:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

So I think a portion of this is my fault so maybe I can try and help out here.

The change here was made because some devices (SolidFire being the only one that's asked for it) do native 4K block sizes, and in order to work in OpenStack without this change need to set 512 byte emulation.

Using the native 4K provides a performance gain and is preferred.  In the SolidFire case this is on a volume-per volume basis.

I don't know of any other back-ends that need/want to take advantage of this currently although I expect that to change now that the option exists and as we roll to newer versions of libvirt.

I thought that the info provided here was pretty clear, and would prefer not to go into real detail in the general docs.

I'd propose that detailed information for each driver that takes advantage of this to fill in the gaps in their doc sections.  Having a brief description here seems best to me in order to make sure folks writing/integrating drivers are aware that the option exists, but leave it to them to determine how it's utilized (conf file, volume-type or other)."}, {'account_id': 321, 'date': '2013-10-02 01:11:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: No score

I do think there should be a little bit more detail about how to troubleshoot an I/O error due to block size issues. How about: 

"If you see any I/O errors when attaching a volume, it is possible that that the backend driver needs to be configured for a custom block size, or that you are running an older version of libvirt (version 0.10.2+ is required for backends that set a custom block size). Block Storage supports custom block sizes on KVM and QEMU. "'}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2013-10-02 17:54:30.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-02 18:04:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

commit_message:
Make wait_for a separate shell script

wait_for() function is used in both init-keystone and devtest_seed.sh,
but the latter doesn't import its definition, so running of this script
leads to "wait_for: command not found" error.

wait_for() can actually be made a separate shell script to make it possible
to use it from any other script (because we add the scripts/ dir to PATH).

Fixes bug 1234704

Change-Id: Id5017e1d4b660a58a9dd75e6e18450744d3399a7

commit_message:
Job configs based on job type

 * Job config defaults are taken from
 Savanna and there is a field with
 autocomplete to fill config property
 * Contribute configuration to launch job

Partially fixes: Bug #1228138

Change-Id: I3f343bfc6eec244d53d703533436c98d4b2ba414

commit_message:
Add auth_uri in conf to avoid unnecessary warning

Unittest code for auth_token.py doesn't specify auth_uri in conf,
which will cause lots of warnings, since auth_token.py will use
'%(protocol)s://%(host)s:%(port)s' to generate auth_uri when it is
None, we can specify this value directly to avoid unnecessary warnings.

Closes-Bug: #1219493
Change-Id: I26b636bcddabd91b06479c6a42a6a48d74ac9431

commit_message:
Disable lazy gettext

This change disables lazy gettext functionality in Keystone,
due to problems with character encoding and logging
detailed in bug 1225099.

It is part of a series of commits across all projects with
lazy gettext enabled.

Change-Id: Ia934a7df9386baf6ae8eb9ff48c24386c47ecd23
Partial-bug: 1225099

commit_message:
Trusts for longrunning tasks

Create trusts from current user to savanna user when cluster is created,
auth savanna user with trust,
use savanna user with trust for nova and cinder, when cluster is deleted

Implements: blueprint trust-for-scaling-and-edp-operation

Change-Id: I558acc01f2663c11879846a51edbf8043ec42676

commit_message:
BigSwitch: sync state on disassociate floating ip

Sends the state of port's parent network to the backend controller
when a floating IP is disassociated from a port.

Closes-Bug: #1235074
Change-Id: I8375e6564b5d08f1adc7e7aef6affc97c8d03c5e

commit_message:
Libvirt: fix defaulting dev bus for block devices

Libvirt driver would try to decide the device bus (in case it was not
specified or not a valid value) based on the device name. This can fail,
but the possible failure wasn't taken into account.

This patch makes sure that if the bus cannot be decided base on the disk
bus passed - it will be decided based on the device type which is always
present.

Closes-bug: #1234311
Change-Id: Ieba23de5f8993989dae761cf6a38f38d2b51a2e6

subject: Allow relative imports in flake8
messages:
[{'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-09-27 16:07:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

run_tests.sh shouldn't be running different things than tox.ini. Lets fix that, and we won't have to remove an important hacking rule check from our entire code base."}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-09-27 16:10:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Is it important though? PEP8 says this is OK.'}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-09-27 16:36:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

OpenStack does not just use PEP8. We use flake8 and hacking, and H302 is part of hacking. We do this in our automation so we can spend a minimal amount of time ever discussing these rather bike-sheddy things. I won't share my opinion on H302, but only on the principles behind hacking/flake8/pep8: the more we diverge, the more we open the door for discussion that is not useful for the project.

Note that run_tests.sh is also not the way the gate runs syntax checks, which is why you're having to fix this. More divergence from conformity leads to more unnecessary work. However, I understand that run_tests.sh is important to some, so if that is what is broken, that is what should be fixed."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-27 18:15:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Works for me

Build succeeded.

'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-09-30 11:33:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I wasn't referring to pep8 the linter tool, I was referring to PEP 8, the document that defines the accepted/recommended practices for the Python community: http://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0008/#imports"}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-09-30 16:19:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Right, I wasn't referring to the tool either, because we don't just apply PEP8."}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2013-10-03 15:20:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

FWIW, it seems this is required to get things in contrib that are reasonably test-able while still working at runtime. If Openstack at large would have a problem with it, I say we just document why we diverge and entertain alternative solutions.'}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-10-03 15:34:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Randall, we control what we want gated and not gated. We have already left out contrib from the "pep8" tox task. Whether or not this was by accident or intentional, it appears that we want to keep it that way.

My suggestion for a fix to this is:

1) add # noqa to the relative imports in contrib resources
2) add contrib/rackspace to the pep8 task -- fixing any noted problems which there should be almost none since these were developed with the same checks turned on.

That way we can never have another formatting discussion about contrib resources again, as it is rather nice not having them about things in heat/'}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2013-10-03 21:09:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

An alternative fix is here https://review.openstack.org/49635"}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-10-03 22:53:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Do not merge

The noqa/tox.ini fix has been merged, and addresses the issue.'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-10-04 13:20:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

Excellent, thanks everyone!'}]

using the run_tests.sh script gets lots of errors from flake8. Therefore,

commit_message:
Allow relative imports in flake8

Modules in /contrib require relative imports, with the result that anybody
using the run_tests.sh script gets lots of errors from flake8. Therefore,
disable the check. PEP8 actually allows relative imports now anyway:
http://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0008/#imports

Change-Id: I6ea3b07d40021bf560946d7febd72c0396e39859

commit_message:
Fix region name in neutron metadata_agent

This was being set wth a incorrect case causing attempts to access
metadata on the overcloud to fail with
EndpointNotFound: Could not find Service or Region in Service Catalog.

Change-Id: I5cd5d2bb4c884e511c31248b1f7213f4287da905

commit_message:
Add back rpc_notifier when ceilometer is enabled

This is to reverse what looks like collateral damage from change id
Ic375272b751159a64777ca73c1b64515195aacfb.

When the Ceilometer service is enabled, we also need to tell nova what to use to send
notifications.

Change-Id: I0015194cfa819e89ef85eae5020fedd6e7d71894
Closes-Bug: #1231158

commit_message:
hyperv tests: replace assertEquals with assertEqual

In Python 2.6, both assertEqual and assertEquals are
convenience aliases to failUnlessEqual.

In Python 3, failUnlessEqual is explicitly deprecated.

Change-Id: I912b2748b9f2b7dc671b2b10b02b820475ced35c

commit_message:
Update makesystem for usig of fuel-ostf-tests repo

config.mk:
* Change using of OSTF repos to FUEL_OSTF_REPO
* Change usgae of Plugin and tests sha to FUEL_OSTF_COMMIT origin/master

repos.mk:
* Change build repo to build fuel-ostf repo from one repo

packages/eggs.module.mk:
* Change eval func to build fuel_ostf egg from fuel-ostf repo

Change-Id: I295de3feb5eff339a4c4d39dbbee1718a4d07c8a
Fixes: OSTF-237

commit_message:
Fix numbering in devtest doc

The "source cloudprompt" step is messing up the numbering of the
online documentation.  I believe that's because of the lack of
indentation on the command (which I assume should remain commented
out since it's only supposed to be run once), so this just adds
indentation.

Change-Id: Ib926a001ee2fbca4e7dae2d5563121795a5cfdaa

[{'created': '2013-10-04 07:48:12.000000000', 'message': "Fix broken solidfire create-snapshot

A previous change to enable secifying size for cloned volumes
created introduced a bug that breaks the ability to create-snapshots
when using the SolidFire driver
(CID: I5628c7fa922780d6b0601e2daa79310a61085edc).

The problem is that we use a shared method in the SF driver for both
create-clone and create-snapshot, the added change only considers the
clone case and does a get ref['size'] but in the case of snapshots
this needs to be ref['volume_size'].

Change-Id: I50603b3ac43f2c3c7e7811ec34de078a268519f7
Closes-Bug: 1234970
(cherry picked from commit 3cd27defb1c820ceadd8bbc6bfd5a405a7376cdb)
"}]
commit_message:
Fix broken solidfire create-snapshot

A previous change to enable secifying size for cloned volumes
created introduced a bug that breaks the ability to create-snapshots
when using the SolidFire driver
(CID: I5628c7fa922780d6b0601e2daa79310a61085edc).

The problem is that we use a shared method in the SF driver for both
create-clone and create-snapshot, the added change only considers the
clone case and does a get ref['size'] but in the case of snapshots
this needs to be ref['volume_size'].

Change-Id: I50603b3ac43f2c3c7e7811ec34de078a268519f7
Closes-Bug: 1234970
(cherry picked from commit 3cd27defb1c820ceadd8bbc6bfd5a405a7376cdb)

commit_message:
Generate interfaces file before cloud-init runs

Cloud-init needs to query the metadata server after the network
interfaces are configured. The upstart job "cloud-init-nonet" is
specifically in place to provide a hook to block cloud-init from
running while we rearrange network interface configurations.

Fixes bug #1233577

Change-Id: Ib5cf75d858fdb670b2abcc082e912c4644d6b169

commit_message:
Breakdown Stylesheets into Logical Parts

Here are the different fixes:
    - misc file has been deleted, we do not need a file where trash is
hidden.
    - creation of pie_chart component, style has been extracted from js
,some refactoring for class name has been done.
    - workflow has been moved to modal.
    - creation of message component.
    - rickshaw.css has been moved out of dashboard in lib/css
    - layout has been changed to _layout, _style and _utils have been
move out of vars, these files do not belong to components, maybe the
less directory root is the best choice.

Change-Id: Ic8b542b312179fe296eb26cdb5a1b45aad401f67
Implements: blueprint css-breakdown

commit_message:
catch MalformedEndpoint exception during catalog creation

At the moment a malformed URL breaks the Keystone API and
makes the Keystone API unusable.

This patch simply excepts the MalformedEndpoint exception,
logs a warning message and continues the catalog creation.

fixes bug #1230279

Change-Id: I4868dda6dd958815964a7a1efa7b67e35d0d732a

commit_message:
Skip test_volume_boot_pattern test for known issue

When booting from volume, the injecting data will failed
due to the nbd attempting to connect to instance disk which
doesn't exist, the consensus is to skip this test until
the bug #1190583, #1155713 is resolved.

Change-Id: I5fafadf08f40bba57f24b693b1789a58d5114f91
Related-bug: #1190583
Related-bug: #1155713

NetApp vserver/vfiler api tunneling in concurrent requests
can cause routing request to incorrect servers in race conditions.
This fixes the api and driver for the mentioned situations.

Closes-Bug:#1176759
'}]
commit_message:
NetApp server tunneling fix

NetApp vserver/vfiler api tunneling in concurrent requests
can cause routing request to incorrect servers in race conditions.
This fixes the api and driver for the mentioned situations.

Change-Id: I607f09e6b7cdfb122d4220b9cbe5ae95464c64f2
Closes-Bug:#1176759

commit_message:
NetApp:iSCSI drivers reserved percent need to change to 0

The iscsi drivers reserved percent is 100 as of now. This needs
to be changed to 0 for default values. It needs to be corrected
so that filter scheduler does not discard netapp backend.

Change-Id: I154fb4d6cc7f1f4dad58b66ab4879b508506ab78
Closes-Bug:#1182015

commit_message:
Add a task identity

Instead of always referring to tasks by name
it is much nicer to refer to tasks by identity
and only refer to by name when this is required.

To fulfill this concept assign each task an identity
where the identity is composed of (name, uuid, version)
where the first two elements are required and the version
is not required.

Change-Id: I55947c79e01c2b2e256bf59186ec0b17d1a27c8f

commit_message:
Replace assert_ with assertTrue

The method assert_ has been deprecated since python 2.7.
http://docs.python.org/2/library/unittest.html#deprecated-aliases

This patch is a mere sed replace of one-liner assert_ to assertTrue.

grep -lR "assert_(" nova/tests/* | \
xargs sed -ri 's/(\W+self.assert)_(\()(.+)(\)$)/\1True\2\3\4/'

Change-Id: I64b9764e1607a46877dad466a4be81e07bdf6f9a

commit_message:
Using the root user for tempest run

The tempest debug info on test case failure feature will require,
sudo permissions. So tempest will run in the 'root' user name,
instead of 'stack'.

Tempest is going to run commands as root in order to gather more,
information about tricky failures. The results will be logged to the
regular logging targets.

devstack-vm-gate.sh removes the ALL command sudo permission from the
stack user in order to avoid introducing root-wrap related bugs.
Only the ``foo``-rootwrap commands remains allowed to the ``stack`` user.

Running tempest as root looks strange, but it does not expected to cause
issues, otherwise a much more complex logic required.

Change-Id: I263adbbbccaccf848cb7116f239d2aab366e0093

commit_message:
Do not check for id in the keystone output

keystone catalog output, when using the non-sql "catalog"
backend, does not contain an id attribute. So don't require
it. Checking for publicURL is probably a good idea instead.

Change-Id: I5f302cf09eeac77b3f448a4e16a3bd97b7bcaaa4

commit_message:
Allow region override for url_for

If region is passed in to url_for use that, otherwise continue
to use the region from the user's session.

Fixes bug #1231171

Change-Id: Ia7d2a4f12a3c0d4d45bb918255184d1736f5bddf

commit_message:
Use mock to do unit tests for ipminative driver

The ipminative power driver uses mox to do the unit tests.
Now the OpenStack is moving to use mock instead of mox in order
to be ready for python 3. This patch changes the test cases for
ipminative driver from using mox to mock.

Change-Id: I9a337c4f38a364a64d61669b045a9610f9c59d42
Closes-Bug: 1231601

A previous change to enable secifying size for cloned volumes
created introduced a bug that breaks the ability to create-snapshots
when using the SolidFire driver
(CID: I5628c7fa922780d6b0601e2daa79310a61085edc).

The problem is that we use a shared method in the SF driver for both
create-clone and create-snapshot, the added change only considers the

commit_message:
Fix broken solidfire create-snapshot

A previous change to enable secifying size for cloned volumes
created introduced a bug that breaks the ability to create-snapshots
when using the SolidFire driver
(CID: I5628c7fa922780d6b0601e2daa79310a61085edc).

The problem is that we use a shared method in the SF driver for both
create-clone and create-snapshot, the added change only considers the
clone case and does a get ref['size'] but in the case of snapshots
this needs to be ref['volume_size'].

Change-Id: I50603b3ac43f2c3c7e7811ec34de078a268519f7
Closes-Bug: 1234970

commit_message:
Error if arguments are not supplied for rename commands

This changes behavior from:
$ cinder rename volume1
$

to

$ cinder rename volume1
ERROR: Must supply either display-name or display-description.

for both 'rename' and 'snapshot-rename'.

Change-Id: I675a3b1428a7fe10653394c80e4a5a473e14c740

commit_message:
Add [sql].connection as deprecated opt for db

The database configuration would not allow 'connection' option in
the [sql] section as a deprecated option for 'connection' in the
[database] section.

Keystone currently uses 'connection' in the [sql] section, so if
we want to use oslo.db in Keystone then it will need to support
'connection' in the [sql] section for existing users.

Change-Id: Id876781a6ee508abb4565c25c59058be74392e64

commit_message:
Add 'set -eu to devtest_.sh'

Just like devtest.sh we want to use 'set -eu' to help detect bugs.
-e exits out if a pipeline returns a non-zero status
-u exits out on unset variables

Change-Id: I2dae00bf912a6d767deb63b9d4f9d1bf02b4dd6d

commit_message:
Fix another remaining use of PIP_INDEX_URL.

Scripts directly embedding a manual pip url break elements like pypi
which offer a local mirror, and that plays havoc with offline builds -
they stay rather more online than desirable :).

Change-Id: I2edf05f0144e11158756125af6afbf63efc5ee95

commit_message:
Create a Http object only when needed

The previous patch that just cleaned up connection pool
does not seem to be enough. This patch goes a bit further
to create a Http Object only when needed

Closes-Bug: 1229475

Change-Id: I1b0a068257ad7882a0235ce48a691652df9c1253

commit_message:
Synch up with OSLO-Incubator

Wanted to get updates before next push to pypi.

The main thing driving this is we're now calling in
some methods from strutils and gettextutils that don't
have the py33 updates.

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-17 16:20:46.000000000', 'message': "Implement qos support

This patch enables Cinder v1/v2 QoS API support, adding following
subcommands to cinder client:
 * create QoS Specs
  cinder qos-create <name> <key=value> [<key=value> ...]
 * delete QoS Specs
  cinder qos-delete [--force <True|False>] <qos_specs>
  'force' is a flag indicates whether to delete a 'in-use' qos specs,
  which is still associated with other entities (e.g. volume types).
 * update QoS Specs
  - add new key/value pairs or update existing key/value
   cinder qos-key <qos_specs_id> set key=value [key=value ...]
  - delete key/value pairs
   cinder qos-key <qos_specs id> unset key [key ...]
 * associate QoS Specs with specified volume type
   cinder qos-associate <qos_specs_id> <volume_type_id>
 * disassociate QoS Specs from specified volume type
   cinder qos-disassociate <qos_specs_id> <volume_type_id>
 * disassociate QoS Specs from all associated volume types
   cinder qos-disassociate-all <qos_specs>
 * query entities that are associated with specified QoS Specs
   cinder qos-get-associations <qos_specs_id>
 * list all QoS Specs
   cinder qos-list

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ie1ddd29fede8660b475bac14c4fc35496d5fe0bc

commit_message:
Implement qos support

This patch enables Cinder v1/v2 QoS API support, adding following
subcommands to cinder client:
 * create QoS Specs
  cinder qos-create <name> <key=value> [<key=value> ...]
 * delete QoS Specs
  cinder qos-delete [--force <True|False>] <qos_specs>
  'force' is a flag indicates whether to delete a 'in-use' qos specs,
  which is still associated with other entities (e.g. volume types).
 * update QoS Specs
  - add new key/value pairs or update existing key/value
   cinder qos-key <qos_specs_id> set key=value [key=value ...]
  - delete key/value pairs
   cinder qos-key <qos_specs id> unset key [key ...]
 * associate QoS Specs with specified volume type
   cinder qos-associate <qos_specs_id> <volume_type_id>
 * disassociate QoS Specs from specified volume type
   cinder qos-disassociate <qos_specs_id> <volume_type_id>
 * disassociate QoS Specs from all associated volume types
   cinder qos-disassociate-all <qos_specs>
 * query entities that are associated with specified QoS Specs
   cinder qos-get-associations <qos_specs_id>
 * list all QoS Specs
   cinder qos-list

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ie1ddd29fede8660b475bac14c4fc35496d5fe0bc

commit_message:
Add some docs on how to setup Ceilometer to use Alarms

We need to use Ceilometer's mongo backend if we want to use
alarms as the sql backend is missing a feature.

Works around bug #1223710

Change-Id: Ib569cfd650ce14480496530e7bbf1b2f71a24c02

commit_message:
HOT str_replace default to empty string for param

If a str_replace param cannot be resolved or is None,
substitute an empty string in order to prevent raising
an exception during validate.

Closes Bug: #1234390
Change-Id: Ica6b84cfc2157b4e1f561f737e9aa67b9f6018ca

commit_message:
_error_in_logs function of driver.py shall check all nodes

1. Don't simply return, if one node is clean or not clean.
2. It's better to log all errors and return all errors.

Change-Id: Ib0e23bff013836347f90bed50dd1d3a9566e6bad
Close-Bug: #1229957

[{'created': '2013-10-02 22:03:02.000000000', 'message': "Handle test_list_servers_by_changes_since without tenant isolation

The test_list_servers_by_changes_since test fails when running with
allow_tenant_isolation=false because there is an arbitrary 2 minutes to
determine the timedelta for the changes-since in the query. That doesn't
work when the servers created in the test are all under the same
user/tenant because the tearDown doesn't block until the servers are
deleted.

This patch makes the timedelta code smarter in that it narrows the
changes-since down to when the test case started setting up the servers
for the test and when it does the query.

Closes-Bug: #1195309

Change-Id: Ie848637ea490da2151e5db8292726111d45a8c2d

commit_message:
Handle test_list_servers_by_changes_since without tenant isolation

The test_list_servers_by_changes_since test fails when running with
allow_tenant_isolation=false because there is an arbitrary 2 minutes to
determine the timedelta for the changes-since in the query. That doesn't
work when the servers created in the test are all under the same
user/tenant because the tearDown doesn't block until the servers are
deleted.

This patch makes the timedelta code smarter in that it narrows the
changes-since down to when the test case started setting up the servers
for the test and when it does the query.

Closes-Bug: #1195309

Change-Id: Ie848637ea490da2151e5db8292726111d45a8c2d

commit_message:
Simpler API to load flows into engines

Previously to run a flow client code had to put together the flow,
an engine, logbook, flowdetail, and storage backend. This commit
adds two helper functions, run() and load(), so that simplest usecase
now looks like

    taskflow.engines.run(flow)

Client code may also provide configuration for storage and engine if
needed, but if not needed it just works with defaults.

Engines are loaded via stevedore, as drivers in 'taskflow.engines'
backend. Now three entry points are defined in that namespace:
- 'default', for SingleThreadedActionEngine, used by default;
- 'serial', as another synonym for SingleThreadedActionEngine;
- 'parallel', for MultiThreadedActionEngine.

Closes-bug: #1224726
Change-Id: I7f4cb5c8ff7f5f12831ddd0952c202d2fd8cd6ef

commit_message:
Ensure SSL CA certificates are installed for curl

On openSUSE, ensure that the ca-certificates-mozilla package is
installed to avoid curl aborting with

  curl: (60) SSL certificate problem: unable to get local issuer certificate

when trying to download the pip source tarball.

Change-Id: Iaf74204ea5330e9abf56f6c9d5a0f9d83992aa59

commit_message:
Don't bail when setting up horizon on openSUSE

I85325179f1792d985b0375572abfe8c8a82fecc3 accidentally removed the
conditional branch required to prevent setup of horizon aborting on
openSUSE, so put it back in.

[{'created': '2013-10-01 16:52:11.000000000', 'message': "Show where files are copied for sudo switch to stack user

The home directory for the 'stack' user defaults to /opt/stack, which is
not obvious to devstack newbies, and can also be overridden by exporting
a value for DEST.  Therefore it's friendlier to be explicit about the
location of this home directory, to which devstack is copied before
being run as the 'stack' user.

Change-Id: Ia1941a5f2f8cf86a06681e85da52b817a855b8ff
"}]
commit_message:
Show where files are copied for sudo switch to stack user

The home directory for the 'stack' user defaults to /opt/stack, which is
not obvious to devstack newbies, and can also be overridden by exporting
a value for DEST.  Therefore it's friendlier to be explicit about the
location of this home directory, to which devstack is copied before
being run as the 'stack' user.

Change-Id: Ia1941a5f2f8cf86a06681e85da52b817a855b8ff

commit_message:
Add benchmark scenarios base class

Every benchmark should be subclass of base.Scenario.
This allows us to implement next things:

*) Auto discovering of benchmark Scenarios
*) Init & CleanUp functionality for benchmark Scenarios
*) All becnhmark Scenarios have built-in os python clients

blueprint test-engine-remove-pytest

Change-Id: I76f70b5bf3d35c3db8bb4d6f94f179c91f6f36a9

commit_message:
Add Timer to rally.utils

This is small and pretty class for with statement that measure time.

Example of usage:

with Timer() as timer:
	#do some dirty stuff
time_in_seconds = timer.duration()

It will be used at least by our Test engine.

Change-Id: I3bf0075df807c2118d5872dd425aae0061232133

commit_message:
Handle Postgres disconnect

If the Postgres server was restarted, database connections would
fail, requiring a restart of the Keystone server.

The disconnect handler for MySQL and DB2 also works with Postgres,
so use it.

Change-Id: I99d8e741d6b5768c9860ed65bdf0c0496211a44d
Related-Bug: #1231657

[{'created': '2013-10-01 21:56:11.000000000', 'message': 'MySQL checkout listener cleanup

The SQLAlchemy engine dialect provides an is_disconnect() function
that returns True when the exception is due to the server going
down. Use this in the checkout listener.

The code in the SQLAlchemy MySQL dialect uses
 errnos = (2006, 2013, 2014, 2045, 2055, 2048) and
 exceptions = (self.dbapi.OperationalError, self.dbapi.InterfaceError)

(See
https://github.com/zzzeek/sqlalchemy/blob/master/lib/sqlalchemy/dialects/mysql/mysqlconnector.py#L113 )

So the new check is similar but the SQLAlchemy MySQL dialect is
probably correct here.

Note that this can also work for other database engines.

Change-Id: Ib55094379f72138ada01c91c7b2b1f79a72ca582
Related-Bug: #1231657

commit_message:
MySQL checkout listener cleanup

The SQLAlchemy engine dialect provides an is_disconnect() function
that returns True when the exception is due to the server going
down. Use this in the checkout listener.

The code in the SQLAlchemy MySQL dialect uses
 errnos = (2006, 2013, 2014, 2045, 2055, 2048) and
 exceptions = (self.dbapi.OperationalError, self.dbapi.InterfaceError)

(See
https://github.com/zzzeek/sqlalchemy/blob/master/lib/sqlalchemy/dialects/mysql/mysqlconnector.py#L113 )

So the new check is similar but the SQLAlchemy MySQL dialect is
probably correct here.

Note that this can also work for other database engines.

Change-Id: Ib55094379f72138ada01c91c7b2b1f79a72ca582
Related-Bug: #1231657

commit_message:
remove test_list_servers_by_changes_since

this test has very poor definition of initial conditions, so can
very easily fail if the nodes are a little slow so the servers
might have been created outside the time window. Also setupClass
really doesn't ensure the initial conditions for this test, as
it ignores some errors.

Remove the test so it doesn't cause issues in the gate, this really
should go back into the unit tests instead.

Change-Id: I5d3e13343045776df18718fdbad512d66de4ceaa

commit_message:
run tempest tests under tempest user

create a new tempest user for running the tempest test suite under,
and give it sudo access to a few network commands so that we can
attempt to debug neutron failures in the gate by dumping out the
state of things.

Change-Id: I5b6f1363a68656b77cebb2096715279180cc9500

commit_message:
Added some optinos to openreviews

* --debug, to set the logging level to debug
* --server, to specify a custom server
* --projects-dir, to specify a custom directory to fetch the projects
  from
* Adapted to the review statuses for gerrit 2.6.1

Change-Id: Id06f0cde90c675210fb0e19ed8bda98e8e76beca
Signed-off-by: David Caro <dcaroest@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Allow to specify custom horizon.tables.DataTable template

This fix allows user to provide his own template in Meta inner
class of DataTable's subclass (and thus extend or completely
override the default 'horizon/common/_data_table.html' template).

Change-Id: I1d1a7b2bf74dcaaee7a7096521853920feb40b21
Closes-bug: #1233609

commit_message:
Open Icehouse development

This should be accepted/merged once all the RC1 bugfixes are in.

This bumps the target version to 2014.1, effectively opening the master
branch to Icehouse development, ending the feature freeze.

The Havana release branch is cut from the previous commit in master.

Change-Id: Id33ea4faa8497f636999583781f652e3e4ac9c21

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-03 17:19:10.000000000', 'message': 'Fix libvirt test on systems with real iSCSI devices

The test_libvirt_kvm_iser_volume_with_multipath_getmpdev() test
expects a system with no real iSCSI devices. It actually triggers
an os.walk() of /dev/disk/by-path/ip-*, which will return any
iSCSI devices on the system. Since the test expects none, this
will cause the test to fail.

This patch just stubs that out to return an empty list always.

Change-Id: Ibb3fd18207d013c35487a3eebb336b5f288b703a
Closes-bug: #1234834
'}]
commit_message:
Fix libvirt test on systems with real iSCSI devices

The test_libvirt_kvm_iser_volume_with_multipath_getmpdev() test
expects a system with no real iSCSI devices. It actually triggers
an os.walk() of /dev/disk/by-path/ip-*, which will return any
iSCSI devices on the system. Since the test expects none, this
will cause the test to fail.

This patch just stubs that out to return an empty list always.

Change-Id: Ibb3fd18207d013c35487a3eebb336b5f288b703a
Closes-bug: #1234834

commit_message:
py33: iteration order of dict is unpredictable

In Python 3.3, hash randomization is enabled by default. It causes the
iteration order of dicts and sets to be unpredictable and differ
across Python runs.

Sort the metadata.keys() in reverse order to keep the test cases as is.

Close-Bug #1233405

Change-Id: I6251f18c9bc3a7842be9efeb5131c82919020e75

Clean CONF out of brick iser

This is part 2 of the work needed to
remove CONF from the brick subproject.

This patch removes CONF from the iser
portion of brick

Fixes Bug #1230066

commit_message:
Log if a quota_usages sync updates usage information

There's some periodic quota_usages syncing that can occur to help
correct any drift that may happen.  It would be useful to log when that
occurs as it may indicate an issue somewhere.

Change-Id: I5b90ab42059ae8ebd0c3890accafb98e70ed037e

commit_message:
fix(wsgi): Non-ASCII characters in the queue name trigger 500 status

The problem was that queue_name wasn't being validated before being
used to construct log messages. Also, I found that the regex used to
validate queue names was not reliable and needed to be rewritten.

Upon further investigation, I also discovered that the queue name
wasn't being validated for all routes that included it. This was
also fixed. Validating all input is a basic best practice re
application security.

Along the way, I edited the validation error messages for clarity,
and relocated the ValidationFailed exception since it is only used
by the transport driver.

Change-Id: Idf9f6c7b9a88865a6396dfcd72abbce96c774490
Closes-Bug: 1208873

But from a deployer's perspective this clearly appears to be a deficiency (i.e. a bug)."}, {'account_id': 6094, 'date': '2013-10-03 15:48:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I want to put the points from the perspective of customer and not to think as a developer to NFS related code in cinder. Customers look a feature as the exposed api in cinder. The fact that cinder create has --image-id as a parameter is supposed to work consistently with different block storage backends whether its iscsi or nfs or any other, its all expected to give the same result. While this is true for iscsi back end its not for nfs back end and hence a customer feels this as a bug and so should we. We should not be dividing it between iscsi world and nfs world and adding standard features to them during different time frames to keep the block storage api consistent which is what cinder is about, hence I strongly feel that this is a severe bug which needs to be back ported to grizzly.'}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2013-10-03 16:23:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Frankly I don't have any issue with the content of this patch, however we've had rules for stable-main releases for a couple releases now.  There have been multiple vendors that have wanted to backport feature / bug fixes like this (including myself) and it's been rejected because due to the rules set up by stable-maint for backports.

Based on the precedent and the rules as they're stated I have to say this doesn't qualify.

Like I said, personally and technically I could care less, but I also don't want to open the flood gates for the other 15 drivers that *forgot* to test or implement features in the last release.  If it was a bug, and not an oversight that would be different."}, {'account_id': 6094, 'date': '2013-10-03 17:01:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

Could not get approved from core. No option.'}]

commit_message:
NFS implement copy_image_to_volume and copy_volume_to_image

The mentioned methods are part of iscsi drivers which is
a block storage driver. It makes customers assume that the
feature is part of block storage drivers in grizzly
and so it appears to be broken when implementation is not
found in nfs drivers. This fix makes the block storage api
consistent for nfs drivers wrt the above methods.

Change-Id: I798fc9d21a41e8bb16915e7b711014cc24346405
Closes-Bug:#1177288

commit_message:
Bugfix public network creation

Altered the command to check for the public network to guard
against a failed command due to network errors or timeouts. Now
we will only examine the list of networks returned if we successfully
retrieved a list of networks to begin with.  We don't worry about
false positives because this is normally run when an installation is
first instantiated so there should be few if any other networks.

Change-Id: I55cc3e569afebcf6b06a5cd0d3c962da35474579

commit_message:
Remove deprecated NVP options

In Havana, NVP configuration was simplified;
in the process a few options that existed
in Grizzly or older were deprecated. This
change removes those options from the Icehouse
tree.

Fixes bug #1221840

Change-Id: Id83a339c88ec2477718a350b6ac1678ccba01509

commit_message:
Reserve 10 migrations for backports

Reserve 10 migrations so that we have the option of backporting fixes
that include a db migration to the stable/havana branch.  We did this
same thing to allow backports to stable/grizzly in
b52a2157bedba693c5da7dcb783b7a151769d6b1.

The choice of 10 migrations is just a magic number.  We haven't used any
of the 10 reserved for stable/grizzly backports, so 10 seems to be
enough.

Implements blueprint backportable-db-migrations-icehouse

Change-Id: I2c5f2e5a966cfffa4a3e54e17fde07a52295f658

commit_message:
feat: add logging to proxy

Adds reasonable logging to the proxy, especially at the transport
layer and for cache debugging.

Mostly imitates the logging style used by the queues server.

Change-Id: If5490a3b18bf660e9c7a57f47959eedacc936b48
Closes-Bug: 1230379

commit_message:
Replaces mox with mock for ipmitool driver unit tests

OpenStack is moving unit tests from mox to mock for python3 compatibility.
This replaces mox with mock for ipmitool driver unit tests.

Fixes bug: #1229396

Change-Id: Ifbb9121fad78674002653502dd6f6c7f2bee3f5e

commit_message:
Rename start_power_state_change to change_node_power_state

Change the name of this RPC method to be a more accurate description
of its function: it is an asynchronous "cast" which changes the power state
of the specified node.

Change-Id: I2c45470ef27e0e74a28ff44428a70fbfac3ee978

commit_message:
Fixes ceph backup import errors

For some reason, using non-rbd volume driver whilst using
Ceph backup causes what looks to be a cyclic import error.
Ensuring that the backup.drivers.ceph module is imported
into volume.drivers.rbd ONLY if it is needed i.e. if both
drivers are in use, seems to remedy this.

Change-Id: Ieae0c3451cfb1750eca8cfcde5e0be9e7eb028d0
Fixes: bug 1231412

commit_message:
Put in place framework for import/export

A zonefile controller has been added to support importing and exporting
zonefiles. The root controller has been modified to include the new
zonefile controller.

Change-Id: I74f7e1103ca61058b64f45f29c45075089765f9f

Implemented zone export

Change-Id: I6177af026e9c4a1040fc9cc567b75a12e47b7726

Added dnspython to requirements

Zone import will need dnspython to parse the zonefile in the request
body.

Change-Id: I80d3587e4194789aee58418fd7aa9b892d2b7521

Zone import working

Change-Id: I88bbb7392bb12b3edb0eb149302805edecef9120

Added comments

Change-Id: I9a32062f9f58d41c1a53f03240a20f0ef04ba441

Better handling of imported NS records

NS records for the origin were added as servers, while other NS records (ie,
delegations) were ignored. This commit fixes that by creating NS records in
Designate for delegation NS.

Change-Id: Iae241829ca1581462df300b64b7392ebbbf9fd9a

Fixed a typo

Change-Id: Icf74e6d265a40e4b1c873d8bc363156cc3f52227

Added better handling of failed records importing

Before, if creating a record failed, the zone would be left in a half-created
state. With this error handling, if creating a record fails, the zone is deleted
and the original exception is raised.

Change-Id: I83f13447cc1ebc9dd5b4c111611d3c842e18f3fc
