revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-03 13:26:00.000000000', 'message': 'Avoid mutable default args in _test_populate_filter_props

Using [] as an argument means that any changes to that argument
will stick across multiple calls to the method.  In this case,
this is surprising behavior that may lead to confusion as we
reuse this method in more tests.  Instead, set it to None, which
is non-mutable, and later assign it to [] inside method scope.

Change-Id: I9cc07b8917ad096c5efea9282bae08c41d15f1cf
'}]
commit_message:
Avoid mutable default args in _test_populate_filter_props

Using [] as an argument means that any changes to that argument
will stick across multiple calls to the method.  In this case,
this is surprising behavior that may lead to confusion as we
reuse this method in more tests.  Instead, set it to None, which
is non-mutable, and later assign it to [] inside method scope.

Change-Id: I9cc07b8917ad096c5efea9282bae08c41d15f1cf

@Bob - I really like the idea of having some sort of safety net for catching plugin incompatibility issues, however, I think the integrity check is an overkill at this point. Let's just have a version string first, and if an integrity check is required, we could add that as well. Other than that, some technical comments on re-raising and raising the internal xapi exception, and one of the cases is not covered I think. integrity check - YAGNI, KISS

Maybe we should inline the version as a string to the plugin? one less file.'}, {'account_id': 475, 'date': '2013-09-24 17:56:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

Mate:

Heh, it was my recommendation that it be a separate file.

The idea was that, when bumping the version, you wouldn't have to touch the file containing the implementation, making the review very easy/safe.

Now that the code is *much* simpler, I don't think it's as important, so could go either way on it."}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2013-09-27 09:49:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: (7 inline comments)

I like the idea.

I really want to see a (unit) test to check the content of the version file equals the variable in the driver. Otherwise, we will probably just forget that.

I think the version scheme should follow a pattern we have already, like the RPC versioning and object versioning. Myself, I would bump the major number for a in-compatible change, or the minor for a backwards compatible change. Then the version check can just ensure the major numbers are equal, but the minor number of the plugin could be greater, thus allowing for more seamless upgrades, when its possible.

It would also be good to add something into the pep8 checker that ensures if a plugin is changed that this version changes, but thats a 'stretch' goal. Or at least raise a bug to track that."}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2013-09-27 09:49:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
XenAPI: Add versioning for plugins

Because the plugins live on a host seperate to Nova we need an interface
to test whether they are the expected version.  We can't use pip or other
requirement systems as they are cross-machine.

Closes bug 1226622

Change-Id: I58ab669061f51bd87071e2cf0d93d33021001309

After taking down the veth link between the physical bridge and the integration
bridge call udevadm settle to wait for any udev events to be completely

commit_message:
Avoid race with udev during ovs agent startup

After taking down the veth link between the physical bridge and the integration
bridge call udevadm settle to wait for any udev events to be completely
processed by the operating system before recreating the veth pair.

Some distributions (e.g. openSUSE) have udev rules installed by default that
call e.g. ifdown <interface> during the remove event. If that is processed
after the ovs agent already brought up the veth pair again the veth pair's
link will be down after the agent completed startup and networking will be
broken for all VM instances.

Change-Id: I95520ea96a9804c5261a0c994bbca137535cc37c
Closes-Bug: #1218556

commit_message:
Switch agent report_interval option to float

Being able to set report_interval > 0 and < 1 makes
it easier to consistently reproduce rpc race
conditions.

Change-Id: I4d907159147177e98b043e7e800aea5cf8c23103
Related-Bug: #1224001

commit_message:
Impl multitenancy support

* tenant_id added to instances and nodegroup-like objects
* tenant_id will be accessibly only inside conductor
* enable tenant-specific model_query by default
* add missed not None checks to sqla/api
* ctx is now passed instead of module in savanna/service/instances.py

Fixes: bug #1218452

Change-Id: Icb0c089fd47dd422fe0c93781d3a5747eb995615

Interesting question though, should the new migration be sqlalchemy-migrate or alembic based?

IIUC we agreed once the issues with alembic were identified that all further migrations for havana would revert to using sqlalchemy-migrate, and that we'd add no further new ones based on alembic.

However that approach might introduce an ordering issue in this case.

Cheers,
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2013-10-01 16:36:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

eglynn, i do vaguely remember the sql-migrate/alembic discussion as well. i'm not familiar enough with migration process to comment on how ordering works between the two but i think it should be safe either way (using alembic or sql-migrate) as i don't think we've edited this column yet.  i'm ok to implement either way as long as we have consensus."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-01 17:46:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Doesn't seem to work

commit_message:
Remove djblets package from murano-dashboard.

Use horizon.tables package instead for drawing the tables (old term is
datagrid).  Now columns attribute is configurable in Service
YAML-markup (it should be consistent with initial data for
table). Last thing to be done is to somehow employ Actions from
horizon.tables (if this can be done at all) - this eliminates need in
custom js-code which adds and deletes table rows on client-side.

Change-Id: I6e6cd41b717d48eafd7e4a5e1fc907d2f1ebf12d
Closes-bug: #1234194

commit_message:
Function synchronization utility

The patch introduces a wrapper for an asynchronous function call that turns
this call into a synchronous one. The wrapper assumes that the called function
immediately returns an object for which it takes some time to get to the
'ready for use' state.

Change-Id: I5a9182e2218112b65b58f478d1d5b51f58b05e16

commit_message:
Removing a needless verification test

The patch removes the needless "test_snapshot" verification test from
the list of available tests as it was added for demonstrative purposes
only as is alredy included in the 'smoke' package of tests.

Blueprint test-engine

Change-Id: Id99b7c2968a3228336e2e90656053daa0413a32f

commit_message:
Added some options and pep8 compliance

- Added the --server option to the cli scripts
- Added the --debug otion too
- Added the --projects-dir option
- It was not detecting correctly the type of code review for gerrit
  2.6.1
- Preserved backwards compatibility

Change-Id: I0a380f293b1d4e0f7afdcf3573f578e6a36985fc
Signed-off-by: David Caro <dcaroest@redhat.com>

commit_message:
add greenthread.sleep to increase yields

This is a stopgap Havana release.  Add eventlet greenthread.sleep to
increase thread yields.

Partially fixes: 1230407
Partially fixes: 1224001

Change-Id: I18953cf8e457ebb33780817582b4788fb5ed6f73

commit_message:
Allow to handle objects in different high-level directory

Added 'store_policy_idx' in request headers from proxy-server
do indicate the storage policy.
Replaced static DATADIR with dynamic headers in obj-server
thus proxy-server could read/write different locations on disk.

Change-Id: Iefdc79098b80445242e3d7da2c78287f7eb8de40

commit_message:
db2 does not allow None as a key for user_id in user collection

mongodb allows None value as a key for _id field, but db2 does not.
this patch will fix the problem when meters coming with user_id
being set to None.

fixes: bug #1234165
(cherry picked from commit 77a0603bebcb25fba94ddfb40e50baed46eb9384)

Change-Id: Ifcb8e20c3be0ed224f2d2b77dcd0f99a63688762

commit_message:
Return 401 when action is not authorized

When a user is not authorized to access to something is the API,
this one return 401 instead of 400 now.

Fixes bug #1232045

(cherry picked from commit b2df5f9013f6d30097d5841027a759af0e9c8002)

Change-Id: I421c36d6d3f143abd22d193de412c63edccb7175

commit_message:
Unskip test_tokens and update expected status to 404 from 401

Now that the API results in a 404 for an invalid x-subject-token
and a 401 for an invalid x-auth-token, we need to update the expected
resulting HTTP Status from 401 to 404 in the test_tokens test.

closes-bug: 1221889
Change-Id: I158c968c1948ee658305e9ec484425d98f187cba

commit_message:
Remove unecessary `get_boolean` function

`get_boolean` is entirely equivalent to `bool_from_string` so just use that
instead.

Change-Id: I3cdcea2db882d49f6b4208ea579cff6f898c29e2

commit_message:
Open Icehouse development

This should be accepted/merged once all the RC1 bugfixes are in.

This bumps the target version to 2014.1, effectively opening the master
branch to Icehouse development, ending the feature freeze.

The Havana release branch is cut from the previous commit in master.

Change-Id: Ib18965c2ddafc18167d15f7a53f618cdf3c75a30

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-20 19:56:23.000000000', 'message': "Make Instance.refresh() extra careful about recursive loads

This simply makes sure that the instance copy that we fetch to
refresh an instance can not trigger lazy loads itself due to
a bug in get_by_uuid() or below. This hasn't actually been the
cause of any recent bugs, but this makes it much more careful.

It also makes sure that obj_load_attr() refuses to do its work

commit_message:
Make Instance.refresh() extra careful about recursive loads

This simply makes sure that the instance copy that we fetch to
refresh an instance can not trigger lazy loads itself due to
a bug in get_by_uuid() or below. This hasn't actually been the
cause of any recent bugs, but this makes it much more careful.

It also makes sure that obj_load_attr() refuses to do its work
if self._context is None, which was previously only being
enforced for remoted calls.

Change-Id: I76f433af34620045b079e0a2c30c60b28a4ce525

Keeping this in mind, I think that it might be a good idea to put the validation pieces somewhere in common where both the service code, and the guest agent can pull them from.

That said, I'm open to discussing any other approaches that you may have in mind.

Cheers,

commit_message:
Check whether volume_id and snapshot_id is None

During validating, resource state is (INIT, COMPLETE), volume_id get
from `Fn::Att' is '', previous validation logic treats this as a
invalid value.

While, Ref return resource name instead if it found resource_id is
None, validation logic can pass with Ref.

The solution here determines whether volume_id is None.

Fixes bug #1230140

Change-Id: I483da691fb59fd5c03315b69857af5ada2f6d826

Gary, a few points:

1. RBD volume are currently striped, using the default of 
   4MB objects. You highlight a good point that there is no 
   way to alter the striping parameters used when creating 
   volumes and I think it would be a good idea to add that 
   in.

2. The volume api must be driver agnostic so adding 
   striping params to the api is not likely to get in unless
   there is a general requirement for it. If we decide to go
   down the route of allowing striping params to be provided
   by the client then volume metadata might be a better means
   but I can't see a need to specify this info on a per
   volume basis. I think allowing these values to be defined
   in cinder.conf should suffice.

3. When restoring rbd volumes from backup it would be great
   to be able to ensure that the stripe settings used is the
   same as is currently not the possible.

4. If you are going to add columns to the db you needs a new
   migration schema version."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-10-03 06:03:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

and stripe_unit parameters which are then used to create the volume.

Adding RBD data striping capabilities to OpenStack (python-cinderclient)

commit_message:
Adding RBD data striping capabilities to OpenStack (Cinder)

blueprint rbd-stripe-parameters

When creating an RBD volume, various command line options can be specified;
two of these relate to data striping and are stripe_count and stripe_unit.

stripe_count: specifies the number of objects to stripe over before looping back to the first object.
stripe_unit: specifies the stripe unit size in bytes

Takes the RBD stripe parameters from python-cinderclient and simply passes them through the many
methods calls present within the files below:

cinder/api/v1/volumes.py: retrieves and enters stripe_count and stripe_unit to volume_api.create

cinder/volume/api.py: create method parameters modified to include stripe_count and stripe_unit;
these are also included in the 'create_what' directory to be entered into the database.

sqlalchemy/models.py: ensure Cinder knows stripe_count and stripe_unit columns are present

cinder/volume/flows/create_volume/__init__.py: ExtractVolumeRequestTask.__call_ method parameters
modified to include stripe_count and stripe_unit etc.
stripe parameters entered in the database within EntryCreateTask.__call__

Most modifications are made within the rbd driver cinder/volume/drivers/rbd.py:
* Temporarily reverted to the older method of creating RBD volumes as passing stripe parameters
using self.rbd.RBD().create results in the error InvalidArgument: error creating image.
* As such the size variable has been modified so the correct size of volume is created when using
the older method of volume creation.
* The volume creation unit test with test_rbd.py has been temporarily disabled to account for the
 older method of volume creation

When the error passing stripe parameters to self.rbd.RBD().create is solved, the most recent version
of creating RBD volumes will be adopted and unit tests can be re-enabled.

To allow the switchable fields to appear via Horizon when creating a volume, cinder/volume/manager.py
has been modified to create a volume type cinder.volume.drivers.rbd.rbddriver when only the RBD driver
is in use and is deleted otherwise. The user selects this volume type and can then enter the stripe_count
and stripe_unit parameters which are then used to create the volume.

This implementation requires:
Adding RBD data striping capabilities to OpenStack (Horizon)
Adding RBD data striping capabilities to OpenStack (python-cinderclient)

Change-Id: Ic9f6e6bdee3952f8b728a9cdf9903cf95eba004e

The current patch addresses several comments:

A test for the migration script has been added.

The encryption key id is stored in the backup table, instead of relying on the source volume.  If the source volume no longer exists, the encryption key id and volume type id will still be stored in the backups table.

The volume type is only required to be the same between the source volume and the destination volume if the source volume type is an encrypted type.  If a restore to a different volume type is attempted when the source volume type is encrypted, an exception is raised.  If the source volume type is not encrypted, then a restore to a different volume type is allowed to occur.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-23 17:29:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Works for me

commit_message:
Add backup support for encryption metadata

This modification allows the encryption key UUID field,
which has been added to the volume table, to propagate when
backups are made of encrypted volumes and then restored. It
also includes an addition of the encryption key UUID to the
backups table.

Implements: blueprint encrypt-cinder-volumes
Change-Id: Ia5c0f0e8a905c555ab879f32ae23bec8cd64fc38

commit_message:
Support per-MechanismDriver config with ML2

This commit adds support to devstack to set per-MechanismDriver
configuration when running with the ML2 Neutron plugin. Allows
for arbitrary MechanismDriver configuration with no additional
changes to devstack as MechanismDrivers are added to ML2.

Implements blueprint ml2-devstack-mechanism-driver

Change-Id: Iedff731fbbe319df1478db6f40a29d387747e554

help the VM check if the target host has enough memory for this

commit_message:
Add ignore_memory_check option for live migration

Now, when live migrate instance with target host, conductor will
help the VM check if the target host has enough memory for this
live migration.

But this check is not always needed, as when user using RamFilter
with ram_allocation_ratio greater than 1, then the target host can
be overcommitted.

The fix was leave the decision to cloud admin to decide if memory
checking is needed by a new option ignore_memory_check. If set to
True, then memory checking will be ignored; otherwise, conductor
will help check if there are enough memory on the target host.

Fix bug 1214943

Change-Id: I2bfe941197aa72d5252e76b7e5dcf61b70277524

commit_message:
Hot software config configsets translation

This patch takes care of one aspect of the blueprint i.e. to translate
software component script keys (files,packages,commands) to configsets to
process different configurations.

Implements blueprint hot-software-config

Change-Id: I6d733b2db19ef8ef9d3515cbfc0527eb2a9717fc

commit_message:
Support limit in keystone.users.list

Now keystone.users.list(limit=1) can return the limited
user(s).

Fixes: bug #1079154

Change-Id: I98cef3da51df6c71f6c7313b6b6fed978e125714

commit_message:
Add support for querying the quotas usage

QuotaSetsController's _get_quotas already supports querying for
the usage. This patch allows sending a parameter "usage" to the
REST API when asking for quotas

Change-Id: I2103f41ae7aac1ed9f071949db4fb205552694f5

commit_message:
VMware ESX: Fixes vol clone & clone from snapshot

The driver was earlier performing create from a source volume and create from
a snapshot point by copying the source volume container folder.

This is not valid in case of vSAN datastore where the volume data is not a
'file' in the container folder unlike VMFS/NFS datastores. So copying folder
will only copy descriptor file and hence the source and cloned volume will
end up writing to the same data location, eventually corrupting it.

The fix is to copy only the VMDK file (descriptor + data) and not the entire
container folder. The implementation does the following:
1. Create a volume backing
2. Delete the current VMDK
3. Make a copy of source volume's VMDK file to the destination using virtual
   disk manager. In case of create from snapshot, we copy the VMDK file
   corresponding to the snapshot point.

Fixes bug: 1233034

Change-Id: I51c9870c11a6d66f9f47c1ad9aaa2abc3dd0533a

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-11 16:09:15.000000000', 'message': "Add key manager implementation with static key

Per feedback received on other patch sets, an example key manager
driver is required to support ephemeral storage encryption and
Cinder volume encryption. The ConfKeyManager class reads its key
from the project's configuration file and provides this key for
*all* requests. As such, this key manager is insecure but allows
the aforementioned encryption features to be used without further
integration effort.

To clarify the above statements, the configuration-based key
manager uses a single, fixed key. When used to encrypt data (e.g.,
by the Cinder volume encryption feature), the encryption provides
limited protection for the confidentiality of data. For example,
data cannot be read from a lost or stolen disk, and a volume's
contents cannot be reconstructed if an attacker intercepts the iSCSI
traffic between the compute and storage host. If the key is ever
compromised, then any data encrypted with the key can be decrypted.

This commit copies the ConfKeyManager class from Nova as well as
synchronizing a few minor changes to the key manager interface in
Nova.

Implements blueprint encrypt-cinder-volumes
SecurityImpact

Change-Id: I5cb06386410f46cabc490fa6af23272d1d2cb979

"}, {'created': '2013-09-12 17:03:46.000000000', 'message': "Add key manager implementation with static key

Per feedback received on other patch sets, an example key manager
driver is required to support ephemeral storage encryption and
Cinder volume encryption -- see
* https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/encrypt-cinder-volumes
* https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/encrypt-ephemeral-storage
The ConfKeyManager class reads its key from the project's
configuration file and provides this key for *all* requests. As
such, this key manager is insecure but allows the aforementioned
encryption features to be used without further integration effort.

To clarify the above statements, the configuration-based key
manager uses a single, fixed key. When used to encrypt data (e.g.,
by the Cinder volume encryption feature), the encryption provides
limited protection for the confidentiality of data. For example,
data cannot be read from a lost or stolen disk, and a volume's
contents cannot be reconstructed if an attacker intercepts the iSCSI
traffic between the compute and storage host. If the key is ever
compromised, then any data encrypted with the key can be decrypted.

This commit copies the ConfKeyManager class from Nova as well as
synchronizing a few minor changes to the key manager interface in
Nova.

Implements blueprint encrypt-cinder-volumes

"}, {'created': '2013-09-13 14:00:00.000000000', 'message': "Add key manager implementation with static key

Per feedback received on other patch sets, an example key manager
driver is required to support ephemeral storage encryption and
Cinder volume encryption -- see
* https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/encrypt-cinder-volumes
* https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/encrypt-ephemeral-storage
The ConfKeyManager class reads its key from the project's
configuration file and provides this key for *all* requests. As
such, this key manager is insecure but allows the aforementioned
encryption features to be used without further integration effort.

To clarify the above statements, the configuration-based key
manager uses a single, fixed key. When used to encrypt data (e.g.,
by the Cinder volume encryption feature), the encryption provides
limited protection for the confidentiality of data. For example,
data cannot be read from a lost or stolen disk, and a volume's
contents cannot be reconstructed if an attacker intercepts the iSCSI
traffic between the compute and storage host. If the key is ever
compromised, then any data encrypted with the key can be decrypted.

This commit copies the ConfKeyManager class from Nova as well as
synchronizing a few minor changes to the key manager interface in
Nova.

Implements blueprint encrypt-cinder-volumes
SecurityImpact

Change-Id: I5cb06386410f46cabc490fa6af23272d1d2cb979

commit_message:
Add key manager implementation with static key

Per feedback received on other patch sets, an example key manager
driver is required to support ephemeral storage encryption and
Cinder volume encryption -- see
* https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/encrypt-cinder-volumes
* https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/encrypt-ephemeral-storage
The ConfKeyManager class reads its key from the project's
configuration file and provides this key for *all* requests. As
such, this key manager is insecure but allows the aforementioned
encryption features to be used without further integration effort.

To clarify the above statements, the configuration-based key
manager uses a single, fixed key. When used to encrypt data (e.g.,
by the Cinder volume encryption feature), the encryption provides
limited protection for the confidentiality of data. For example,
data cannot be read from a lost or stolen disk, and a volume's
contents cannot be reconstructed if an attacker intercepts the iSCSI
traffic between the compute and storage host. If the key is ever
compromised, then any data encrypted with the key can be decrypted.

This commit copies the ConfKeyManager class from Nova as well as
synchronizing changes with the key manager interface in Nova.

Implements blueprint encrypt-cinder-volumes
DocImpact
SecurityImpact

Change-Id: I5cb06386410f46cabc490fa6af23272d1d2cb979

commit_message:
Remove need for CONF acces in brick iscsi

At some point we'd like brick to be a standalone lib,
and as such we don't want to have a requirement for
CONF files and having duplicate conf entries across
projects.

The better approach would be to let the projects decide
what they want to use, and how they want defaults to be set
and then pass those settings in via __init__ or when calling
the methods that need them.

Partial-Bug: #1230066

Change-Id: Ib108f1abb2948cb896bdad58070daa7a725a205d

commit_message:
Quotas roll back failure of create volume task

Fixes quotas rollback issue if volume creation fails

* Added revert method in QuotaCommitTask to rollback
* volume reservations.

Fixes bug #1230176

Change-Id: I0983ea876983b4294ed0aebb49a065715a185b4e

commit_message:
Open Icehouse development

This should be accepted/merged once all the RC1 bugfixes are in.

This bumps the target version to 2014.1, effectively opening the master
branch to Icehouse development, ending the feature freeze.

The Havana release branch is cut from the previous commit in master.

Change-Id: I32a2ef85a8dff2b3a681fe7b33fc5dc983b7ab81

commit_message:
Heat: use first_address instead of first_private_address

first_private_address no longer exists in OS::Nova::Server
as it was a misconceived feature.

Change-Id: Id1a0eeca1bf3b57c27e6b93ae64e11d3de9b771e
Related-Bug: #1228929

commit_message:
xenapi: set dhcp timeout on VM installation

Set the DHCP timeout to 120 seconds during virtual machine installation.
Some users failed to run devstack, due to a low DHCP timeout setting.
The default value is 60 seconds. This change sets the value to 120 secs,
that should give enough time for most people.

Change-Id: I15fde45ed0d005c1a8621134eee6c3c338b5be5d

commit_message:
Adds ExternalIpAddressExhaustedClient exception

Adds the ExternalIpAddressExhaustedClient exception so
a more specific exception than NeutronClientException is raised
when IPs run out. This will allow for better exception
handling in Nova.

Closes-Bug: 1233143

Change-Id: I9f40bf14eec0f485dfd21b36605a2474b99a8941

commit_message:
Storwize SVC driver hostname can't start with number

Storwize family storage does not allow host identifier start with
a numeric number. Otherwise cinder initialize_connection() API will
throw exception due to such invalid host name in the connector. The fix
is to add a '_' symbol as prefix if the host identifier in connector
starts with non-alphabet letters.

Closes-Bug: #1233952
Change-Id: Ia88afc373e2635c10c3f6256331a4fd90f51f4b8

reads more clearly.

commit_message:
v2 api - return bootable attr value on volume list

Add bootable to the list of values returned by display_list.  This
was returned in v1 api, and is still in v2 header, but was missed
in the new implementation.

Closes-Bug: #1232287

Change-Id: If7460b1c8ab4af417117c4bf6cfdccc5fcf21f46

commit_message:
Should not add metadata filter rules if disable metadata proxy

The metadata filter rules should not be added into iptables if Neutron
metadata proxy is disabled.
This patchset fixes this issue by adding a condition when adding metadata
filter rules to iptables.

Closes-Bug #1224290

Change-Id: I7f14d281c31c1828a90abac8821635773238b2d0

commit_message:
Change DATABASE_HOST default to 127.0.0.1

Attempt to fix what is suspected to be a DNS resolution issue with

commit_message:
Use standard CLI object-verb ordering for alarm-{g|s}set-state

The openstack CLIs all use an object-followed-by-verb ordering
convention when construct command names.

Follow a similar convention for commands to get and set alarm
state.

Change-Id: I34e0f450019556c80476df782d4c86dca08bdc9d

[{'created': '2013-10-02 22:27:57.000000000', 'message': 'Handle BadRequest in VolumeDetachTask

Novaclient raises BadRequest(400) if a volume is already
detached when delete_server_volume is called.

This change treats BadRequest the same as a NotFound in the
VolumeDetachTask, and logs the actual exception string.

Change-Id: I34c01a493e8c87281d2adecb6d4404376cf78738
Closes-Bug: #1232234
'}]
commit_message:
Handle BadRequest in VolumeDetachTask

Novaclient raises BadRequest(400) if a volume is already
detached when delete_server_volume is called.

This change treats BadRequest the same as a NotFound in the
VolumeDetachTask, and logs the actual exception string.

Change-Id: I34c01a493e8c87281d2adecb6d4404376cf78738
Closes-Bug: #1232234

commit_message:
Validate template size during download

The API downloads the entire template before validating it. For a 100 MB
file, this causes the API process to use several hundred megabytes of
memory. If several requests like this come in simultaneously, the API
server will run out of memory.

Closes-Bug: #1233366

Change-Id: I453274d62e71b3f860322dfcd98c2830ef039e9b

commit_message:
Check for backing lun on iscsi target create

Check to verify the backing lun was actually created and not just
the controller lun.  If it was NOT created, attempt to issue
tgtadm --op new to see if we can recover.

If this fails, then we want to actually fail in Cinder rather than
pretending that everything went well, so we'll log the error and raise.

Change-Id: I3cabab0d214c051267638a627664df2b673236e3
Closes-Bug: #1226337

commit_message:
Open Icehouse development

This bumps the target version to 2014.1, opening the master
branch for Icehouse development and ending the feature freeze.

The Havana release branch is cut from the commit preceding this.

Change-Id: I59e298f38bb18acfc42aea7f1de075a212befa51

commit_message:
Avoid spamming conductor logs with object exceptions

Conductor's logs should include tracebacks only when something
unexpected happened, which is why we have the client_exceptions()
decorator. The object_action() and object_class_action() methods
are used for direct remoting of object methods, and thus really
should forward *any* exception to the client.

This patch does that, and also adds missing tests for these two
methods to verify the normal and exception-wrapped behavior.

Closes-bug: #1233789
Closes-bug: #1084706
Change-Id: I505462fa429a6aa68e7b8a08ec2b704bf18d029c

commit_message:
Open Icehouse development

This should be accepted/merged once all the RC1 bugfixes are in.

This bumps the target version to 2014.1, effectively opening the master
branch to Icehouse development, ending the feature freeze.

The Havana release branch is cut from the previous commit in master.

Change-Id: Iff3f857b5e273eec927e2d4f22371c2ae4683ca6

[{'created': '2013-09-29 05:53:17.000000000', 'message': 'py33: uuid verification in find_resource()

1. strutils.safe_encode() return "bytes" in py33.
2. find_resource() makes use of uuid.UUID() to verify the given
uuid argument, uuid.UUID() will trigger TypeError when input is
"bytes".

so, decode the bytes before uuid.UUID() while run in Python 3.

Close-bug #1232445

Change-Id: I504be7b43236b3a4843655706385e506cd559e4e
'}]
commit_message:
py33: uuid verification in find_resource()

1. strutils.safe_encode() return "bytes" in py33.
2. find_resource() makes use of uuid.UUID() to verify the given
uuid argument, uuid.UUID() will trigger TypeError when input is
"bytes".

so, decode the bytes before uuid.UUID() while run in Python 3.

Close-bug #1232445

Change-Id: I504be7b43236b3a4843655706385e506cd559e4e

commit_message:
Update Openstack Common Conf to add Reports

Adds the report module to `openstack.common` in nova (acutally adding
the files to nova's openstack.common directory, as well as adding
the module to the openstack-common.conf file

Change-Id: I5541552688a2fe02b07836cd20a99d727682d808
Implements: bp-guru-meditation-report

commit_message:
Open Icehouse development

This should be accepted/merged once all the RC1 bugfixes are in.

This bumps the target version to 2014.1, effectively opening the master
branch to Icehouse development, ending the feature freeze.

The Havana release branch is cut from the previous commit in master.

Change-Id: Ia3a41177e3c91bd75b38833761f9f8af2b503e4b

vmware driver selection of vm_folder_ref.

causes the vmFolder target in vCenter to be calculated based on the datastore selected

fixes bug: 1214850

commit_message:
Add testing of Neutron per tenant quotas API

The following is added to the Neutron (aka Quantum) API tests:

1) Update to rest client to include methods to invoke the per tenant quotas
API extension as specified in:

http://docs.openstack.org/api/openstack-network/2.0/content/quotas_ext.html

2) New test case to exercise the per tenant quotas API extension

Change-Id: I36df078b51d18c41bf9d9e32a82a073b71128092

commit_message:
Add "note" box callouts to SAIO for user changes.

The SAIO is purpously cut into two parts, so that you don't have to switch
back and forth between root and your unprivledged user.  Add some "note" box
callouts to highlight this changeover.

Change-Id: I8b1a8f0539eac60d4121bdd4dab01df75ecca207

commit_message:
Fix F17 CFN link in Getting Started

F17 CFN links in Getting Started material were no longer valid. The
missing path component (F17) has been added.

As other impacted content is slated for removal this resolves the issue
with the CFN links described in bug #1231310.

Change-Id: I21e1c69aadc4d36b7c3e3e277c01bd80345611b9
Closes-Bug: #1231310

I think it would be worthwhile including a note to highlight the new requirement to set up ALLOWED_HOSTS when using Django 1.5. It's really hard to debug when set up incorrectly and will likely catch people upgrading.

commit_message:
Test cases for V3 Project Actions

This submission adds a new test script "test_projects.py", so as
to verify the CRUD Operations of V3 Projects API. Required support
functions are added in client files under both XML/JSON interfaces.
Added methods to add resources (v3: users, projects, roles) in
DataGenerator class of base.py file.

Implements blueprint: add-keystone-v3-projects-tests

Change-Id: I1a0feb12e9ca503d7a03941b8e5bb1e5ae722fbc

'}, {'account_id': 860, 'date': '2013-09-03 11:12:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

From a Swift point of view, this adds a lot of text to the logs...in some deployments you could push rsyslogd into dropping messages so the swift proxy log would not record transactions.

You could mitigate the Swift issue by logging this information only when you actually validate it with Keystone (i.e., don't log if the token is found in memcache).

I also have security concerns about logging username and token value. See comments from bdpayne in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/33532/ and also see how Swift has handled the security issue with tokens in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/38294/"}, {'account_id': 7701, 'date': '2013-09-04 06:50:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hey thanks for the review.

Understand your concerns about security issues around logging, but this patch does not log tokens or other security vulnerable info, it only logs username, project ID and the corresponding roles. Project ID is logged in several other places as well. Stating the respective userID along with it would help debug issues especially in cases where there are requests spanning across multiple services. 

Also do you think it would be a good idea to change the level of logging to debug, if that would help reduce the number of logs.'}, {'account_id': 860, 'date': '2013-09-06 10:58:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> ...this patch does not log tokens...

You are correct --- I don't know what I was reading!

Using debug level would keep the verbosity down in *my* deployment, so would be welcome, and removes my concern about log sizes."}, {'account_id': 7701, 'date': '2013-09-06 11:27:35.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 860, 'date': '2013-09-06 11:34:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
Log user info in auth_token middleware

Add logging for user information (like user name, tenant_id, roles) in
the auth_token middleware. This would make tracking down issues much
easier.

Change-Id: Ife4ce29d2f8e1a338a025dda4afbd7b563f6b8c1
Implements: blueprint user-info-logging-in-auth-token-middleware

When reporting errors for SLO PUT requests, use the object path from the
manifest without the '/vrs/account' prefix. This is a continuation of

Change-Id: I40c90cccc1b7b5303d9f2b084dccb3be4f4448d8

commit_message:
Simplify object path when reporting SLO put errors

When reporting errors for SLO PUT requests, use the object path from the
manifest without the '/vrs/account' prefix. This is a continuation of
the same changes made for SLO/bulk delete requests in 6768d5b.

Change-Id: I40c90cccc1b7b5303d9f2b084dccb3be4f4448d8

commit_message:
fix: encode keys before caching

This patch addresses an error in the caching layer that prevented it
from playing nice with backends like memcached that expect keys to be
bytestrings rather than unicode strings. The change is made in
oslo.cache to make its use as transparent as possible to users.

Change-Id: Iee48e16393321ff7908807a9f0f7fa20480ec5f4
Closes-Bug: 1230556

commit_message:
feat (proxy/admin): allow partition modifications

This patchset adds one new method to the partitions API
- PATCH /v1/partitions/{partition}

The partitions storage layer is also updated to support a simpler
update interface:
- update(self, name, **kwargs) [with kwargs in ('hosts', 'weight')]

The partitions transport layer is cleared of cruft and reuses JSON
handling utilities from the queues transport layer.

This patch implementation uses jsonschema to achieve self-documenting,
strict format validation of the incoming input.

The partition storage controllers are modified accordingly, as are the
tests. More tests are added for the partitions transport layer to
verify the correctness and to ease future refactorings.

Change-Id: Ifa92b1225421196f95131c2b74e3c07b07c4cfd4
Implements: blueprint placement-service
Closes-Bug: 1230841

commit_message:
Allow slightly older dnspython (>= 1.9.4).

This has a couple benefits.

First, it means Ubuntu Precise users can just install python-dnspython
from packages instead of having to pull one in from source. This
should also fix an install error with new SAIO boxes where running
"python setup.py develop" fails unless a satisfactory dnspython is
already installed.

Second, it matches the dnspython dependency in the global
requirements. This means that the gates are already running with this
dnspython dependency, and it means our requirements.txt is one step
closer to being a subset of the global requirements.txt, which is
important to some people.

Change-Id: I5d58f488e1e4c4139c9fb20d89f386cab1537e98

commit_message:
Validate force_host_copy API param for migration

For the force_host_copy parameter of volume migration, make sure that we
get a boolean or string that we can convert to boolean.

Change-Id: I7a77ca1780a4ef80bc351aa89df0efaaea0d7cf4
Closes-Bug: #1232698

First off I am excited to see this land.  This looks pretty good and it is certainly needed.

The way things look right now it seems that you get the schema and write it to disk every single time that v2 is used.  Then you read it back in at a later point.  If you are going this route why write to a file at all?

However, I would like to see if so that you only get the schema under 1 of three conditions:

1) the cache file is not there
2) a --get-schema flag is provided
3) a error that relates to a API mismatch is found

Is that possible?"}, {'account_id': 5347, 'date': '2013-08-23 16:02:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Thanks for the comments John.

Yes, I had been planning to optimize the caching a bit more and was hoping this patch would bring out some ideas for that. That's why I'm writing it to disk, but was debating when would be the best time to refresh it. Only if missing, on demand, once per day / week / month?

1 and 2 are certain doable, and along the lines of what I was considering anyway.

I'm probably being a bit dense, but I'm not quite sure I understand what you mean in your 3rd scenario. Can you give a specific use case?"}, {'account_id': 6493, 'date': '2013-08-24 00:31:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I was thinking that when the schema in cache was incorrect it would cause improper usage and thus it would be an indication that it may be time to update it.  However I can see how this may be tricky.  I would rather see this patch land sooner than get hung up on finding the perfect times to update.'}, {'account_id': 5347, 'date': '2013-08-26 19:36:42.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-26 20:17:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Works for me

This looks great and I really want to get it in soon.  A couple of minor things.

i assumed that I could run --get-schema without any other option and it would just fetch the schema.  Packagers might want this so that help is readily available.  This brings up another issue, should there be a search path for this information?  If not found in ~/ should the client look in /etc?  Note that I do not think this point should hold up this patch, possibly just a future feature.

Some of the options on V2 do not quite match v2:

v1: --disk-format v2: --disk_format
v1: --container-format v2: --container_format

pretty much everything with a - is a _

In create I get the following when I use --file:

$ glance --os-image-api-version 2 image-create --name hello_world --file X
Request returned failure status.
403 Forbidden
Attribute 'file' is read-only.
    (HTTP 403)

The help message does not make it clear what file is for.

In v1 image-update takes ID as a position argument, in v2 it is a flag with --id.  I prefer v1's way and I think it should be consistent.

One this I tried when I tested this out was creating an image with no disk format, then uploading the image.  I got an error message (which was good).  Then I tried to update the image with the disk format but it failed with a cryptic error:

glance --os-image-api-version 2 image-update --id 295adaea-ea26-482f-9360-3f227f98ba47 --container_format bare --disk_format qcow2
Request returned failure status.
400 Bad Request
Operation objects must contain exactly one member named "add", "remove", or "replace".
    (HTTP 400)

Any thoughts/doc on how that should work?'}, {'account_id': 5347, 'date': '2013-09-04 12:16:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Thanks John!

A couple of those points are due to how the help and options are directly generated from the schema. e.g. the underscores come straight from there. I was avoiding trying to mess with what comes from the schema as much as possible. That said, changing the '_' to '-' is still a simple matter.

The thing with '--file' is certainly misleading. I suppose I need to filter out the read-only attrs from the schema (of which file is one). Again, I was trying to avoid putting too much knowledge of the actual schema in there, but in this case I think it's going to be necessary since that is indeed a bit confusing.

The error with update is going to require some investigation. Offhand it sounds like the json patch isn't being correctly formed."}, {'account_id': 4463, 'date': '2013-09-04 14:30:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Upon discussion with Eddie we realized that the issue is that the json schema does not explicitly specificy which properties are read only. Instead of having two "sources of truth" namely the client and the glance api telling you which are the readonly or reserved properties, maybe the first step towards this could be making the json schema more descriptive and specify which properties are readonly. 
But we should be looking on the side at a more long term solution for conveying this information'}, {'account_id': 5347, 'date': '2013-09-04 14:42:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

To expand on what Iccha said, specifically we're thinking the immediate solution is to add to the 'description' field text indicating read-only properties as this is just human-readable. There *is* a "readOnly" attribute defined in the json hyper-schema extensions, but at this point in time we don't want to risk breaking other things and thus will propose adding this feature in the next release cycle (Icehouse).'}, {'account_id': 6493, 'date': '2013-09-04 17:47:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

The short term solutions for read-only and the long term plan make sense to me .'}, {'account_id': 5347, 'date': '2013-09-04 19:32:20.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-04 22:03:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Doesn't seem to work

Couple of things based on my observation so far :
(1) maybe --remove should be --remove-property so it indicates its only for additional schema in image-update

(2) The HTTP codes are being swallowed. For example:
iccha@iccha-dev:~$ glance --os-image-api-version 1 image-update ba334a8c-2b15-436e-8a70-10eb6612c222 --disk-format binary

    (HTTP 400)

Unable to set 'disk_format' to 'binary'"}, {'account_id': 5347, 'date': '2013-09-05 16:41:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Changing the --remove sounds good.

As for the error, it isn't swallowing HTTP codes because in this case, there isn't one. In V1, that validation occurred on the server. But in V2, the validation happens in warlock against the schema. Unfortunately warlock DOES swallow the actual validation error and returns it's own generic error. Might be able to address this by overriding warlock's setter. Or perhaps write our own warlock like class - it's little more than a convenience wrapper around a couple other libs that do the validation and patch creation."}, {'account_id': 4463, 'date': '2013-09-06 15:08:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

commit_message:
Add CLI for V2 image create, update, and upload

Provides command line support for image-create, image-update,
and image-upload using the Glance V2 API. This includes building
help text for create and update based on the image jsonschema
as fetched from the server.

Also fixes bug caused by default warlock patch generation not
matching what Glance expects when updating a core property
which had not originally been set when the image was created.

Related to bp glance-client-v2

Change-Id: I841f9e3d05802f4b794cb6f4849abe03ff0324d9

commit_message:
Return 401 when action is not authorized

When a user is not authorized to access to something is the API,
this one return 401 instead of 400 now.

Fixes bug #1232045

Change-Id: I7ef8ed1f7cd40a845bcf860561c2cb7da52fb9e9

commit_message:
db2 does not allow None as a key for user_id in user collection

mongodb allows None value as a key for _id field, but db2 does not.
this patch will fix the problem when meters coming with user_id
being set to None.

Change-Id: If48e5117198f3e9ad834e4f7fa58ec27c57a8bc8
fixes: bug #1234165

commit_message:
Allow to update an alarm partially

The patch allow to only modify a part of an alarm instead of force to
set the full alarm description.

This permit to an application that have been written code around alarm
with ceilometerclient 1.0.4 and ceilometer pre havana-3. To update alarm
without any change with this and ceilometer >= havana-3 (ie: heat).

Fixes bug #1231303

Change-Id: I20250131d05d20bfadbca450dfe6b8237f4b7183

So how does one size the number of connections? It seemed like before if each proxy worker process could handle max_clients = 1,024 concurrent connections, one could theoretically reach 1,024 open connections to N memcache servers (ignoring error cases). Is that right?

Here the default is 2, so max 2 * N connections to the memcache servers.

So how does one determine when this number needs to be bumped up?  Would this not be a similar throttle to maximum concurrency a proxy server process should have?

Thanks for looking into this.'}, {'account_id': 917, 'date': '2013-09-05 01:14:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Peter: This will have to be determined experimentally.  In my testing, having a pool of 1 on my saio is just as performant as the previous implementation.  You could consider the max connections that are set on each memcache server, and divide by the total number of proxy workers to get an absolute max to set.  It would then be a good idea to divide by 2, as reloading a proxy will keep its memcache connections open while it finishes current requests, and then give yourself a little padding :)

Ideally, it would be nice to set it as low as possible without affecting performance, so we will need to do some testing to find what a sweet spot might be fore this.'}, {'account_id': 917, 'date': '2013-09-05 15:49:43.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 917, 'date': '2013-09-05 15:50:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Work In Progress

(3 inline comments)

Overall looks good. Would like to see constants instead of 2, but could be convinced otherwise.

Would love to see tuning recommendations for this, and some assurance that the default value of 2 connections will not throttle behavior.

Was also wondering if we could create a unit test that causes a grow in the original set of connections before this change and show that this contains it."}, {'account_id': 917, 'date': '2013-09-17 22:56:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Hey Peter:

For the config defaults, we don't use constants anywhere else, so just followed conventions.  I can change it if some other change needs to be made, but would prefer to keep things going if we don't need to make changes.

Unfortunately, it will be hard to test the default of 2 until we can get things merged in, though I can imagine we will test it fairly quickly.  As a side note, on a SAIO install, with it set to 1, benchmarking showed little to no difference in performance.  

Some thoughts:  In general, memcache requests are super fast.  Top that with the fact that a production install is likely going to have multiple memcache servers (and the various memcache requests are going to spread across the servers), it is my opinion that in the end it will be mostly a wash.

My biggest concern is that if we set the default to too high, is that it doesn't help with the overall memcache connection issues.

All that said, I'm willing to change it to something else with more thoughts from others."}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-09-17 23:31:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

@Chuck:

Perhaps I am too easily convinced, but that all sounds reasonable. We can adjust during the release candidate time period if need be.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-09-18 20:54:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

I wonder how this will work with high-latency links to memcache servers, like if you've got two DCs that are physically far apart.

In that case, I think I'd want a sort of soft-limit pool, where it'll open as many connections as are demanded, but when the connections get checked back in, it only keeps so many around. That way, if there's a load spike, some requests will get slower while waiting for a new memcache TCP connection, but they won't all back up waiting to get their hands on one of a very few available real connections.

That seems like it'd help with temporary load spikes in a one-DC cluster too. It wouldn't even have to be an overall load spike, just a temporary shift in the memcache key distribution. (I know it's using a strong hash, but that doesn't protect against bad luck.)

I dunno; maybe I'm overthinking things. Just seems like this'll increase the error rate to clients occasionally and unpredictably."}, {'account_id': 917, 'date': '2013-09-18 21:32:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Sam:

You wouldn't want high latency links to memcache, period.  In such a scenario, it would seem better to have two separate memcache pools (one for each dc)."}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2013-09-19 03:50:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

So this highlighted a problem with the memcache client that I was not previously aware of - I'd like to see a testcase that demonstrates this change fixes that - but since creiht didn't write one for me; I'll have to do that before I +2.

I like the idea, tho, if someone else already trusts it - don't wait on me - I also want to get this thing on master so it's easier to try out real clusters where we can find out if this default (which seems low) is really going to make sense or not."}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2013-09-19 19:26:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

@ creiht - what do you think:

http://paste.openstack.org/show/47273/

FWIW: I believe the behavior change responsible for this is that the original set of memcache connections was a list, so .pop() in _get_conns() took the last element off, and .append() in _return_conns() puts it back, so that the next .pop() will get the same connection, hence the behavior was implicitly serialized.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-10-01 01:11:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

I'm not convinced that waiting for the 'set' command is necessary. If we don't wait, there's a chance that, when we go to read the value back, it won't be there because the command hasn't been processed yet. However, if we *do* wait, there's a chance that, when we go to read the value back, it won't be there because memcached dropped it."}, {'account_id': 917, 'date': '2013-10-01 14:51:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

I'm not sure I'm quite convinced either.  Worst case, is *if* this were to happen, it would fall back to getting the data from the source rather than cache.  If we really want to do add more to the memcache set, I feel that it can be done outside this patch."}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-10-01 15:18:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

I don't think the noreply is about it disappearing, it is about the set value appearing at a later time, potentially after its previous value was deleted.

So here is a pseudo sequence diagram for one greenlet using two connections to a single memcached.

 Time  Connection 1   Connection 2   Memcached
 ---------------------------------------------

 t0      set(x, 404)

 t1                     del(x)

 t2                                    del(x)

 t3                     set(x, 200)

 t4                                set(x, 200)

 t5                                set(x, 404)

 t6      get(x)

If the set() is using noreply, then a single stream can see that set come in out of order.

Perhaps there is something else that prevents this?"}, {'account_id': 917, 'date': '2013-10-01 16:01:52.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 11.'}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-10-01 16:09:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

If we had more time, it would be nice to have a unit test that captures the failure sequences we encountered so that we catch future changes that break this.

Looks good otherwise.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-10-01 16:47:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Works for me

commit_message:
Pool memcache connections

This creates a pool to each memcache server so that connections will not
grow without bound.  This also adds a proxy config
"max_memcache_connections" which can control how many connections are
available in the pool.

A side effect of the change is that we had to change the memcache calls
that used noreply, and instead wait for the result of the request.
Leaving with noreply could cause a race condition (specifically in
account auto create), due to one request calling `memcache.del(key)` and
then `memcache.get(key)` with a different pooled connection.  If the
delete didn't complete fast enough, the get would return the old value
before it was deleted, and thus believe that the account was not
autocreated.

ClaysMindExploded
DocImpact
Change-Id: I350720b7bba29e1453894d3d4105ac1ea232595b

commit_message:
NetApp fix clone image compatibility issue with ssc

It makes clone image functionality compatible
with the ssc feature. Hence it makes clone
image sensitive to volume type and provision
on the right share matching volume type
extra specs.

Change-Id: If980239fedf784a1cca7abd6ee3d00f8625b9b11
Closes-Bug:#1226752

commit_message:
After commiting quota we should avoid certain reverts

After we commit the quota successfully we do not want to
set the database volume to destroyed or attempt further
rollback of the quota itself to reflect what the code
previously did.

Closes-Bug: #1230189

Change-Id: I115dc6736b8f2d0d7b2b6f29e9fd1904fd1c6eee

commit_message:
feat: split proxy API into admin and public apps

Rationale: when deploying the proxy, operators should be the only ones
that have access to the administrative functionality - primarily, the
management of partitions. This split makes it possible to deploy the
forwarding portion of the proxy independently of the administrative
portion.

The appropriate changes in tests, setup.cfg, and configuration files
(see: I7cf25e47ecff47934b50c21000b31308e1a4c8a9) were made.

Certain helpers that are reused for wsgi transport implementations
were extracted to a common location to aid reuse.

Unit tests were also simplified for the proxy, with the intent to make
them more thorough in coming patches.

New test requirement: httpretty
- used to perform request mocking during proxy transport unit tests

Change-Id: Ia26981a78c477a896370c48768e71f45c364c769
Implements: blueprint placement-service

[{'created': '2013-09-25 19:44:16.000000000', 'message': "feat: separate config for queues and proxy

This patchset separates the configuration of the proxy from that of
the queues server. This was done in order to simplify the
configuration file for each, and because it is not expected that the
proxy and the queues servers would be launched on the same
host. Furthermore, many of the proxy options are not relevant to the
queues server.

Furthermore, to allow this, common.config had to be modified to take a
prog parameter. This enabled the ability to save multiple
configuration files to one directory. See below for details.

The new files are:
- etc/marconi-proxy.conf
- etc/marconi-queues.conf

They are expected to be saved to one of:
- ~/.marconi
- /etc/marconi

Regarding namespaces, queues specific options are associated with the
'queues:*' group and proxy specific options are associated to the
'proxy:*' group.

The appropriate changes are also applied to the test suite and
helpers.

Change-Id: I7cf25e47ecff47934b50c21000b31308e1a4c8a9
Implements: blueprint placement-service

commit_message:
feat: separate config for queues and proxy

This patchset separates the configuration of the proxy from that of
the queues server. This was done in order to simplify the
configuration file for each, and because it is not expected that the
proxy and the queues servers would be launched on the same
host. Furthermore, many of the proxy options are not relevant to the
queues server.

Furthermore, to allow this, common.config had to be modified to take a
prog parameter. This enabled the ability to save multiple
configuration files to one directory. See below for details.

The new files are:
- etc/marconi-proxy.conf
- etc/marconi-queues.conf

They are expected to be saved to one of:
- ~/.marconi
- /etc/marconi

Regarding namespaces, queues specific options are associated with the
'queues:*' group and proxy specific options are associated to the
'proxy:*' group.

The appropriate changes are also applied to the test suite and
helpers.

Change-Id: I7cf25e47ecff47934b50c21000b31308e1a4c8a9
Implements: blueprint placement-service

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-20 22:01:35.000000000', 'message': 'proxy: mirror structure of marconi queues + bootstrap

This patch adds smarter configuration to the proxy in two steps:

1. mirror the transport implementation used in marconi.queues in
   marconi.proxy
2. add a bootstrap file to take care of start up

Rationale: make configuration work, make deploying easy, make
alternate transport implementations feasible.

Another change: the unit tests are fixed by adding a few changes:
1. add drop functionality to the proxy storage interface
2. use drop/flush in test suite tearDown
3. rm tests.unit.test_config
4. delete queues at the end of the catalogue test (not yet robust)

The rationale for (3) was that test_config did not play nice with
other tests when they were registering their options, and failed as a
result. Furthermore, we should not need to test oslo.config.

Configuration changes: new fields in etc/marconi.conf
- drivers:proxy
- drivers:proxy:storage:{memory.mongodb}
- drivers:proxy:transport:wsgi
- oslo_cache

Finally, redis was removed from requirements.txt.

Change-Id: If2365a1a738a3975fe6bde7bd07dfdee3460cecd
Implements: blueprint placement-service

commit_message:
proxy: mirror structure of marconi queues + bootstrap

This patch adds smarter configuration to the proxy in two steps:

1. mirror the transport implementation used in marconi.queues in
   marconi.proxy
2. add a bootstrap file to take care of start up

Rationale: make configuration work, make deploying easy, make
alternate transport implementations feasible.

Another change: the unit tests are fixed by adding a few changes:
1. add drop functionality to the proxy storage interface
2. use drop/flush in test suite tearDown
3. rm tests.unit.test_config
4. delete queues at the end of the catalogue test (not yet robust)

The rationale for (3) was that test_config did not play nice with
other tests when they were registering their options, and failed as a
result. Furthermore, we should not need to test oslo.config.

Configuration changes: new fields in etc/marconi.conf
- drivers:proxy
- drivers:proxy:storage:{memory.mongodb}
- drivers:proxy:transport:wsgi
- oslo_cache

Also, fix: InternalServerError -> HTTPInternalServerError

Finally, redis was removed from requirements.txt.

Change-Id: If2365a1a738a3975fe6bde7bd07dfdee3460cecd
Implements: blueprint placement-service

commit_message:
Allow Neutron quota driver to be configured

We were hard-coding the quota driver in quantum.conf
by keeping the default commented out. This patch adds
the ability to set the driver.

fixes lp 1234324

Change-Id: Ia90a5afcf550e20bb85fef5ec50f6aa9075992cb

commit_message:
Skip test if sqlite3 not installed

The test is attempting to run the sqlite3 binary during its test run.
Since there's no guarantee that it's installed it should catch an
execution error and skip.

Change-Id: I9f4ed1872fcfe3b8393644a77692dbfcce8ecab2
Closes-bug: 1227868

commit_message:
py33: sort dict for test_add_floating_ip_to_fixed

In Python 3, hash randomization is enabled by default. It causes the
iteration order of dicts and sets to be unpredictable and differ across
Python runs.

Sort the list and update the expecting result.

Close-Bug #1233406

Change-Id: Ib747824dad340534d484797afb87b5e92200e426

commit_message:
py33: 'str' does not support the buffer interface

Binary I/O expects and produces bytes objects. If sys.stdout is
assigned to io.BytesIO, print() output it stdout by default, then
there will be "TypeError".

For this case, mock.patch() decorator can not work well casually.
So this patch just update the six.StringIO() for stdout/stderr.

Close-Bug #1229163

Change-Id: Ieb29ad0774c9b7f2b691628d753b210640baca8d

commit_message:
Add-in some re-auth logic when using os_cache

When using os_cache for the auth_token, if username and password
are available when a token fails to validate/authenticate, attempt
a reauth behind the scenes.

The helper object for stashing the auth_token doesn't handle flushing
the cache.  This is valid behavior because the result would be the
same as if a bad username/password were issued (401 Unauthorized).

Fixes-bug: 1214658
Change-Id: I107fc999610bb7638cefcb5d195aeafdcd663ca6

commit_message:
Add shelve/unshelve/shelve-offload command

The "shelve" API, which powers off and snapshots a vm instance, has been
implemented by Nova-server side.
In addition, thare are two relational API "unshelve" and "shelveOffload".
This patch adds three commands for using these APIs.

Fixes bug #1231827

Change-Id: Ic2ad1bb537efb40a3155e9f3c7b63e09e82be7f1

commit_message:
Add prepare_request function to requests.py

This function is supposed to be called to prepare a request that will be
used later by other parts of this client.

Future patches will more clearly show how this function is meant to be
used.

Implements blueprint python-marconiclient-v1

Change-Id: I08b35996119c4e12c31e3113771390b2ec58dfd3

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-30 05:55:59.000000000', 'message': 'py33: align the order of parameters for urlencode()

In Python 3, hash randomization is enabled by default. It causes the
iteration order of dicts and sets to be unpredictable and differ across
Python runs.

In the test case, the fixed expecting string will not match the test
result, it is relying on the dict order.

This change transforms the input dict to a sequence of two-element list,
with fixed order, and update the related expecitng string.

Close-Bug #1231871

Change-Id: Ia998cdb6978fc024dd0d3c9bd161fbdebe68638a
'}, {'created': '2013-09-30 21:57:01.000000000', 'message': 'py33: align the order of parameters for urlencode()

commit_message:
py33: align the order of parameters for urlencode()

In Python 3, hash randomization is enabled by default. It causes the
iteration order of dicts and sets to be unpredictable and differ across
Python runs.

In the test case, the fixed expecting string will not match the test
result, it is relying on the dict order.

This change transforms the input dict to a sequence of two-element list,
with fixed order, and update the related expecitng string.

Close-Bug #1231871

Change-Id: Ia998cdb6978fc024dd0d3c9bd161fbdebe68638a

If you're running as root, $USER is "root", so you wind up with
"user = root" in all your conf files, which is not what you want.
Now this command interpolates $USER as swift (or whatever

commit_message:
SAIO tweak: get the right username in conf files.

If you're running as root, $USER is "root", so you wind up with
"user = root" in all your conf files, which is not what you want.
Now this command interpolates $USER as swift (or whatever
unprivileged user you have), so you get the right config value.

Change-Id: I7a0829d8a17cb09559dafbf3e305369c3fa6a230

commit_message:
Rebuild HA Guide if files modified

Special case the HA Guide since it is using asciidoc. We do not
check for includes and simply rebuild it whenever a file in the
directory is changed.

commit_message:
Add NovaInstanceWithCinderVolume_Native F18 HOT template.

A template showing how to create a Nova instance, a Cinder volume and attach
the volume to the instance using Cinder VolumeAttachment.
The template uses only Heat OpenStack native resource types.

Change-Id: I07459a76a4ae859e53185c273d1f20a3985cc74d

commit_message:
Purge ubuntu getting started guide of old info

The ubuntu getting started guide has not been maintained, and
most likely no longer works.  We should point people to Debian/Ubuntu
docs when they exist, or the devstack getting started guide.

Change-Id: I27a12b5366739ffcad459706c0712882b89abd2f
Closes-Bug: #1182428

[{'created': '2013-09-25 12:00:57.000000000', 'message': 'py33: unknown encoding: base64 Edit

Python 3 doesn't support str.encode('base64'), we should use the
module "base64" instead.

Close-Bug #1229161

Change-Id: I1432952558f8c5c3cff39761306e91916d80207f
'}]
commit_message:
py33: unknown encoding: base64 Edit

Python 3 doesn't support str.encode('base64'), we should use the
module "base64" instead.

Close-Bug #1229161

Change-Id: I1432952558f8c5c3cff39761306e91916d80207f

commit_message:
Disable lazy gettext

This change disables lazy gettext functionality in Nova,
due to problems with character encoding and logging
detailed in bug 1225099.

It is part of a series of commits across all projects with
lazy gettext enabled.

Change-Id: Ia934a7df9386baf6ae8eb9ff48c24386c47ecd23
Partial-bug: 1225099

commit_message:
Implement threaded SSH for provisioning and Vanilla plugin

 * SSH commands are now run in parallel for both configuring during
   provisioning and for Vanilla plugin configuring

 * Introduced throttling for SSH connections

Change-Id: I88a68642f3649fdab8666e36b4ab226815b72320

This seems wrong to me, however after checking with Mtaylor and others it seems this was the request/recommendation from the foundation and the foundation lawyers more specifically.'}, {'account_id': 8125, 'date': '2013-09-24 04:37:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

1) There's 2 extra files, cinderclient/openstack/common/apiclient/base.py and cinderclient/openstack/common/apiclient/client.py that have both 'LLC' and 'Foundation' listed as copyright holders.  Can these be updated so that the earlier date is simply listed as 'Foundation' and the later date removed? 

2) There's some inconsistency in how these copyright headers are specified, some say "Copyright (c) 2012 OpenStack..." and some say "Copyright 2012 OpenStack..." Can we update them so they either all have a "(c)" or all of them do not?'}, {'account_id': 1207, 'date': '2013-09-25 16:47:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Do not merge

Did we ever get a confirmation off legal that retrospectively changing a copyright is ok to do? I believe it is dodgy in some jurisdictions, but I'm not a lawyer..."}, {'account_id': 6676, 'date': '2013-09-25 16:57:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Michael Davies:

1) we should not directly modify openstack.common files because it should be synced from oslo, i will NOTE this in commit message in next patch
2) yes, you're right the (c) is not used all the time through openstack project, but this patch aims at the trademark from OpenStack LLC to OpenStack Foundation, so it is an unrelated change. but it seems a reasonable change and i think it should take (c) along with Copyright, so i will update this, also will be NOTEd in commit message. thanks

i wii do this in this weekend if i have time (only one single day with other personal stuff to deal with, but i will try, oops). since this is not a urgent problem and core-team may need to ask lawyer of foundation, this patch can wait

thanks"}, {'account_id': 6676, 'date': '2013-09-28 15:16:11.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-28 16:27:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Doesn't seem to work

Instead of setting a object state variable, which makes
a graph_action object now have state we can instead just
have a new event boolean that will be set to true when
a suspension is detected. This value will then be used to
alter the status returned from the parallel graph action.

Also fixes a lack of returned status when there are no

'}]
commit_message:
Avoid setting object variables

Instead of setting a object state variable, which makes
a graph_action object now have state we can instead just
have a new event boolean that will be set to true when
a suspension is detected. This value will then be used to
alter the status returned from the parallel graph action.

Also fixes a lack of returned status when there are no
items to actually run (aka the deps counter dictionary
is empty).

Change-Id: Ifa3ba7293613ba1e70e77d29504ea214f0b4c9e9

commit_message:
A few adjustments to the progress code

Remove an unneeded variable in the tasks class as
well as add a test for capturing and checking on
the progress that is emitted and adjust how the task
action should use a single function for doing state
changes (and another one for saving/resetting). Also
add in progress boundary checking (between 0 and 1).

Change-Id: Ic8cf56e3b25a493129f370b7b52e3cb2238da844

Not all the states are actively being used in any of
the taskflow code, so instead of keeping them around
lets just clean them up.

Fixes: bug 1232168

commit_message:
Improve error feedback

When an error occur instead of just return the HTTP response code the
client will now try to extract the error message that contains the reason
of the problem and show it to the user in a user-friendly way (no codes
at all), the intention of this patch is to improve the usability of the
ironic client. Things like HTTP response codes can still be viewed when
used with the debug mode enabled ( -d ).

Change-Id: Ieca021cc0e0eabe91c13335c3062ef9622da3004

Quotas provide the ability to restrict resources for users and projects.
Keystone is used as central quota storage for all components.
All resources and quota limits are stored in keystone. There are
2 types of quotas - per project quotas (project quota) and per user
quotas (user quota). They limit resources for concrete project and user

Implementation:

Part 1. DB
    Add following tables:
    * resources (register of available resources)
    * project_quota (stores per-project quotas)
    * user_quota (stores per-user quotas)

    Add SQLQuotaDriver driver for resources and quotas management.

'}]
commit_message:
Add OS-QUOTAS API extention: DB

Quotas provide the ability to restrict resources for users and projects.
Keystone is used as central quota storage for all components.
All resources and quota limits are stored in keystone. There are
2 types of quotas - per project quotas (project quota) and per user
quotas (user quota). They limit resources for concrete project and user
respectively.

Implementation:

Part 1. DB
    Add following tables:
    * resources (register of available resources)
    * project_quota (stores per-project quotas)
    * user_quota (stores per-user quotas)

    Add migration to enable database changes.

    Add SQLQuotaDriver driver for resources and quotas management.

blueprint: store-quota-data

Change-Id: Id46f37d5b93b5ee2ee77dcc45659f5e66033ad9b

This patch does integration deploy-helper functions
into PXE driver.

commit_message:
Add tests for api/utils.py

Currently the functions on api/utils.py is not being directly/well tested,
this patch add tests for those functions. This patch also replaces the
current regex to test the patches with a DRYer one.

Change-Id: Ibda84bd759e2a96c76d06465c6d0740d4ddea263

commit_message:
Check for required fields on ports

Currently the API on ports does not check for any required fields,
this patch add such verifications + tests.

Change-Id: I4a2003c3a5ab0a0b31742fcac119fbe20929f636
Partial-Bug: #1223847

Hi Sean, 

I keep thinking about this and I think you are right we need to test at the API level that when the lazy _() function is installed the API returns the translated message from the NeutronException. In fact that test is actually already in here:  https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/neutron/tests/unit/test_api_v2_resource.py#L164

Currently the problem is that we are loading the exception module before we install the lazy _() function, so I actually don't think this needs a test case since it is evident that if the first thing we do when the server starts is install the lazy _() function then it will be installed before the exception module. 

With that, and the additional note explaining this in the code I hope this can be accepted. 

Thank you,"}, {'account_id': 6522, 'date': '2013-09-27 04:56:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/25823/

Seems to suggest that it shouldn't matter where/when '_' is installed, as long as it is before the calling function. 

Also, https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/neutron/tests/unit/test_api_v2_resource.py#L164

Demonstrates that get_localized_message is called, on the versions api. Not the network api, as you have reported."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-27 16:26:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: Doesn't seem to work

"}, {'account_id': 7996, 'date': '2013-09-27 16:32:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Hi Akihiro, I double checked with the other components and it seems that they all install the _() function after importing eventlet, so I am going to move it down to where it was on the previous patch.

Hi Sean, The order actually does matter. In this case the function needs to be installed before the exception module loads so that the message = _() statements are created as Messages, and not as unicode. About the existing test case that test case tests all APIs, the particular exception in this bug gets caught here: https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/neutron/api/v2/resource.py#L85 which is covered by the test case.

Thank you!'}, {'account_id': 7996, 'date': '2013-09-27 16:34:18.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 11.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-27 18:18:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Works for me

commit_message:
Lazy translation _() must be installed earlier than it currently is

Some APIs are not translating because the exception's message field is
unicode() instead of Message.

However, if you look at the tracebacks related to this bug, you'll see them in code paths where it's happening on the *first* use of a neutronclient object.  That seems to indicate that this wouldn't have any affect.

However, if it gets merged, we'll know pretty quickly using logstash if this fixed it or not."}, {'account_id': 5263, 'date': '2013-10-02 15:47:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Verified; Looks good to me (core reviewer); Approved

commit_message:
Forcibly clear connection pool after every request

Neutron client is ending up with bad socket descriptors
which causes the behavior including trying to read from
the socket that amqp currently holds etc. A temporary
solution is to clear the connection pool so we get a
fresh socket built for every request.

Closes-Bug: 1229475

Change-Id: I43b1fe535bc5bd1fc726c97a293bf7912cd7ef1e

commit_message:
Purge Fedora getting started of old info

Remove all of the old tools/openstack related info from
the on_fedora docs - the best source of documentation for
Fedora is now the RDO docs (for Heat RPM package installs),
or the on_devstack guide for development installs.

Change-Id: Id33d94cc063361698eb87315a56ef7f720ecaa73
Partial-Bug: #1182428

commit_message:
Open Icehouse development

This should be accepted/merged once all the RC1 bugfixes are in.

This bumps the target version to 2014.1, effectively opening the master
branch to Icehouse development, ending the feature freeze.

The Havana release branch is cut from the previous commit in master.

Change-Id: Ib8aedc149750ce32558f1fbbf51263f2110be3ac

subject: Raise Babel requirements to >= 1.3
