Hmm, actually, keystone only has Babel>=0.9.6, and some distros still have 0.9.6, so at this point in the cycle it might make sense to stick to >=0.9.6 ?"}, {'account_id': 6593, 'date': '2013-09-30 12:28:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thierry, the dependency in Keystone on 0.9.6 is wrong. when you check gating logs, it uses Babel 1.3 for gating, and it is passing tests on those. when you test against 0.9.6, as we do on openSUSE side, tests are failing.

Babel 1.1 is the first version that passes gating, so it makes sense to require that. it does not work with 0.9.6 anymore. 

I think at this point in time for the release it would make sense to fix the requirements of the packages to match the real requirements the project has.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2013-09-30 13:09:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: No score

commit_message:
Raise Babel requirements to >= 1.3

1.1 is the first version that installs properly with Pip 1.4,
which we require already. Furthermore Keystone now added
a dependency on a newer Babel.

However, 1.1 has a bug so that babel won't compile the zh_CN locale, so
we have to update to the 1.3 version which fixes that bug.

http://babel.pocoo.org/docs/changelog/#version-1-3

Related-Bug: 1232235
Related-Bug: 1233694

Change-Id: I4060a0ca83f82e89c6d5b3e97bafb60e09db542b

commit_message:
Configure CSRF_COOKIE_SECURE & SESSION_COOKIE_SECURE when use_ssl is true.

If an operator is using SSL for Horizon(as they should be), we should ensure the
secure flag is set on the Django csrf and session cookies. This ensures the
cookies are only sent to the server over HTTPS connections (assuming the browser
the user uses respects the RFC)... also the local_settings file suggests the
operators set these to true.

You can read more about the secure flag here:
https://www.owasp.org/index.php/SecureFlag

Change-Id: I92dbaf94c7c4d1070d8a2a9dfc6511c0e88bc2c4

commit_message:
Libvirt: add boot_order to GuestDisk XML

Libvirt allows us to specify the boot order on a guest disk basis, by
adding a boot element with order attribute to the guest disk XML.

This patch adds the ability to render the GuestDisk XML with this
element. It will be used in subsequent patches to allow us to further
customize boot ordering.

Related-bug: 1229327

Change-Id: I7ca620f4ade743e76ad49d402c3a989ffb9efead

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-02 13:23:15.000000000', 'message': "Libvirt: use boot order instead of os_boot_dev

This patch makes the libvirt driver define boot order using boot element
of the guest disk XML instead of the general boot element. The two are
interchangable but mutually exclusive as per libvirt documentation (see
http://libvirt.org/formatdomain.html#elementsOSBIOS for more details).

This makes the boot ordering more flexible and also makes it possible to
boot from a wider range of devices.

This patch does so by making libvirt's image back-end and volume
back-end methods that generate the libvirt XML for guest devices
consider the boot_index information added in
I23f2f7637a6ed023785a0ffde050fbd43402c655. It also removes the
general os_boot_dev from the guest config XML.

Change-Id: I9ddda045eb179a87ed9280926bfacf19550312bb
Closes-bug: 1229327

commit_message:
Libvirt: use boot order instead of os_boot_dev

This patch makes the libvirt driver define boot order using boot element
of the guest disk XML instead of the general boot element. The two are
interchangable but mutually exclusive as per libvirt documentation (see
http://libvirt.org/formatdomain.html#elementsOSBIOS for more details).

This makes the boot ordering more flexible and also makes it possible to
boot from a wider range of devices.

This patch does so by making libvirt's image back-end and volume
back-end methods that generate the libvirt XML for guest devices
consider the boot_index information added in
I23f2f7637a6ed023785a0ffde050fbd43402c655. It also removes the
general os_boot_dev from the guest config XML.

Change-Id: I9ddda045eb179a87ed9280926bfacf19550312bb
Closes-bug: 1229327

Fixes bug #1233882

commit_message:
Remove djblets package from murano-dashboard.

Use horizon.tables package instead for drawing the tables (old term is
datagrid). Now columns attribute is configurable in Service
YAML-markup (it should be consistent with initial data for
table). Last thing to be done is to somehow employ Actions from
horizon.tables (if this can be done at all) - this eliminates need in
custom js-code which adds and deletes table rows on client-side.

Change-Id: I7dba8f2a43538c26d6419a6c2753d2d3ac15e3cb
Closes-bug: #1234194

client side when raised inside of object_class_action.  The conversion
to instance objects resulted in a lot of tracebacks showing up in the
conductor log after a tempest run.

Change-Id: I347737c15f6e0dd5c0e69978f8fd685420abd61c
Closes-Bug: #1084706
'}]
commit_message:
List InstanceNotFound as client exception

Add the InstanceNotFound exception as an exception to be handled on the
client side when raised inside of object_class_action.  The conversion
to instance objects resulted in a lot of tracebacks showing up in the
conductor log after a tempest run.

Change-Id: I347737c15f6e0dd5c0e69978f8fd685420abd61c
Closes-Bug: #1084706

[{'created': '2013-09-27 19:49:51.000000000', 'message': "Change the queue 'broker' config to allow a list of brokers.

For high availability, multiple concurrent queues are required. Hence
a list of brokers could be provided in the Barbican configuration file.
This commit accommodates treating the 'broker' config attributes as a
comma-delimited list of brokers.

Change-Id: Ia48e6483835acc518014f0270bb180e5a5e9f1dd
"}]
commit_message:
Change the queue 'broker' config to allow a list of brokers.

For high availability, multiple concurrent queues are required. Hence
a list of brokers could be provided in the Barbican configuration file.
This commit accommodates treating the 'broker' config attributes as a
comma-delimited list of brokers.

Change-Id: Ia48e6483835acc518014f0270bb180e5a5e9f1dd

commit_message:
Disable lazy translation

Late in the Havana cycle bug 1225099 was found in the lazy
translation code, and to be safe it was decided to disable lazy
translation for Havana. This change does that.

Change-Id: Ia934a7df9386baf6ae8eb9ff48c24386c47ecd23
Partial-bug: 1225099

Update the brick remotefs driver to allow the cinder volume
drivers to pass in backend specific values for CONF options. If
the drivers don't pass in backend specific values fall back to
using the CONF options directly.

Fixes Bug #1230066

Change-Id: Ie37a803dc0f895ffd9dc2c7daf8255e6096ccee2

Remove CONF from brick remotefs

Move the remotefs CONF options back into their
corresponding volume drivers.

Partial-Bug: #1230066

commit_message:
Pass through args and kwargs in brick connectors

This is a change needed to help remove CONF usage
in the brick/remotefs/RemoteFsClient.
RemoteFsClient can then pull the values from the caller.

Change-Id: Ie1ff2a39b92c4150fec4a3191367797a260b30ec
Partial-Bug: #1230066

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-18 11:46:43.000000000', 'message': 'VMware driver: Using RetrievePropertiesEx API

The existing code uses deprecated API RetrieveProperties for querying through
property collector. The public doc asks to use RetrievePropertiesEx instead.

RetrievePropertiesEx works by retrieving results in serveral batches rather than
retrieval in a single API call. This works well in environments containing
large number of VMs or ESX hosts.

There are three steps involved 1. Get first batch 2. Continue retrieving using
a token 3. Cancel retrieval when not needed

Batch size is user configurable, default is 100 results per batch.

Fixes bug: 1227078

Change-Id: I85a6f6a7e2d764b9843efbd0dd347fba3ef19310

commit_message:
VMware: Usng RetrvProprtisEx & does multi ESX scan

The existing code uses deprecated API RetrieveProperties for querying through
property collector. The public doc asks to use RetrievePropertiesEx instead.

RetrievePropertiesEx works by retrieving results in serveral batches rather than
retrieval in a single API call. This works well in environments containing
large number of VMs or ESX hosts.

There are three steps involved 1. Get first batch 2. Continue retrieving using
a token 3. Cancel retrieval when not needed

Batch size is user configurable, default is 100 results per batch.

The review also fixes a careless programming error leading to scanning only
1 ESX host under the vCenter server for datastores.

Fixes bug: 1227078
Fixes bug: 1229654
DocImpact

Change-Id: I85a6f6a7e2d764b9843efbd0dd347fba3ef19310

commit_message:
Add a base transport class

This patch adds a base transport class which should be used by all
transports implementations. The patch also adds a Response class, which
implements a common response object to use between the client API and
the transport API.

Change-Id: I9dff8ed9592076e7bc7da55d7717de2a5829f5f3

commit_message:
Fix devops requirement

1. Use the version tag instead of commit_id
2. Use git+https instead git+ssh for setup devops w/o git+ssh
access

commit_message:
Open Icehouse development

This should be accepted/merged once all the RC1 bugfixes are in.

This bumps the target version to 2014.1, effectively opening the master
branch to Icehouse development, ending the feature freeze.

The Havana release branch is cut from the previous commit in master.

Change-Id: I99861235bb71d9b47ff85623317efe4243ee0668

commit_message:
Imports oslo policy to fix test issues

Tests inheriting from keystone.tests.TestCase depend on having the
policy_file command-line option declared before setUp runs. Importing
the oslo policy module automatically declares the option.

Fixes-Bug: 1233224
Change-Id: I939bbdcb7df1c4a59108dced92d4d5c2e96defe2

commit_message:
Fix add policy missing rule issue

In firewalls/workflows.py retrieve 'rule' instead of 'firewall_rules'
from AddPolciy post message. In test_add_policy_post, we need to
ensure 'firewall_policy_id' field is not set before added to policy.

Change-Id: I5f9ff81f42f4f8c7ce5c638c9074cc2dec4e1434
Closes-Bug: #1231235

commit_message:
Disable lazy translation

Late in the Havana cycle bug 1225099 was found in the lazy
translation code, and to be safe it was decided to disable lazy
translation for Havana.  This change does that.

Change-Id: Ia934a7df9386baf6ae8eb9ff48c24386c47ecd23
Partial-bug: 1225099

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-27 11:21:46.000000000', 'message': "heat_keystoneclient: Fix consuming trusts via v2 API

Contrary to my understanding when I first wrote this code, it is
possible to consume trusts (ie get a trust scoped token) via the
v2 keystone API.  So this patch reworks the heat_keystoneclient
so we consume trusts via the v2 client, and only create a v3
client when required (when creating or deleting a trust), so we
minimise the requests to keystone.  Similarly it's only necessary
to create the v2 client when creating the client object if we
need to consume a trust (and there are no credentials in the
request).

Note this change depends on this patch to python-keystoneclient:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/48462/, so we can't merge until
this gets merged and released.

Change-Id: I61b380bc63d606c128ce029f1960c6812a3324e3
Closes-Bug: #1227901
"}, {'created': '2013-10-01 08:26:29.000000000', 'message': "heat_keystoneclient: Fix consuming trusts via v2 API

Contrary to my understanding when I first wrote this code, it is
possible to consume trusts (ie get a trust scoped token) via the
v2 keystone API.  So this patch reworks the heat_keystoneclient
so we:
- Consume trusts via the v2 client (so we can access the ec2tokens
  extension which is v2-only)
- Only create a v3 client when required (when creating or deleting
  a trust), so we minimise the requests to keystone.
- Similarly it's only necessary to create the v2 client when creating
  the client object if we need to consume a trust
- When a trust is found in the context, we always consume it
- Don't modify the request context, as this has undesired side-effects
  if the context is subsequently used to perform actions which require
  obtaining a keystone token, instead create a context containing a
  trust_id and trustor_user_id when the stack is stored.

Note this change depends on this patch to python-keystoneclient:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/48462/, so we can't merge until
this gets merged and released.

Change-Id: I61b380bc63d606c128ce029f1960c6812a3324e3
Closes-Bug: #1227901

commit_message:
heat_keystoneclient: Fix consuming trusts via v2 API

Contrary to my understanding when I first wrote this code, it is
possible to consume trusts (ie get a trust scoped token) via the
v2 keystone API.  So this patch reworks the heat_keystoneclient
so we:
- Consume trusts via the v2 client (so we can access the ec2tokens
  extension which is v2-only)
- Only create a v3 client when required (when creating or deleting
  a trust), so we minimise the requests to keystone.
- Similarly it's only necessary to create the v2 client when creating
  the client object if we need to consume a trust
- When a trust is found in the context, we always consume it
- Don't modify the request context, as this has undesired side-effects
  if the context is subsequently used to perform actions which require
  obtaining a keystone token, instead create a context containing a
  trust_id and trustor_user_id when the stack is stored.

Note this change depends on this patch to python-keystoneclient:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/48462/, so consuming trusts won't
work unless a version of keystoneclient including this change is
used.

Change-Id: I61b380bc63d606c128ce029f1960c6812a3324e3
Closes-Bug: #1227901

commit_message:
Proxy find_resource_by_name_or_id from neutron client

Change I95a351071e68dfc2d67f3895c87f45ad2221767f gutted quantumclient so
it serves as a proxy for neutronclient, but in the process the static
method find_resource_by_name_or_id was removed. Nova is using
find_resource_by_name_or_id directly so it needs to still exist in
quantumclient and proxy through to neutronclient. This is needed for the
stable branches which are still using python-quantumclient.

Closes-Bug: #1233264

Change-Id: I01b099aa34fedb63967517f288905321816eaf18

commit_message:
Disable lazy translation

Late in the Havana cycle bug 1225099 was found in the lazy
translation code, and to be safe it was decided to disable lazy
translation for Havana.  This change does that.

Change-Id: Ia934a7df9386baf6ae8eb9ff48c24386c47ecd23
Partial-bug: 1225099

commit_message:
VMWare: Disabling linked clone doesn't cache images

This fixes an issue when use_linked_clone is false and the image is
already in the cache.  The problem was that the image would be
copied from glance into the instance directory even if it was already
in the cache.  This change checks if the file is in the cache, only
copies from glance if it is not, and copies the image from the cache
into the instance directory if use_linked_clone is false.

Fixes: bug #1207064
Change-Id: Idfa59eb0eb26cce52ff59f97e433deeab6510215

I really think we should be checking for known errors and retrying (possibly multiple times) after a delay if a known error occurs.

Certainly the code at the moment should have a delay in it - otherwise it'll attempt a rescan _immediately_ after a failed rescan - and if we're asserting that a scan is already running it doesn't give much window for the original scan to finish."}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2013-09-17 10:36:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Bob I am checking for known errors, should I be more specific?

I didn't really want to add a delay. We usually want the SR.scan info straight away. How long should I wait?"}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2013-09-17 10:37:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Bob, I am assert that multiple SR.scans get coallesed into a single attempt that then gets returned together. So when I get the result, the SR.scan has completed, and the operation underneath will probably have completed, but if not, we will now ensure we call SR.scan again, after it has completed anyways.'}, {'account_id': 100, 'date': '2013-09-17 15:34:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Exponential backoff should work well. It could start at something quick (1 second? half a second?)'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2013-09-17 16:02:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Yeah, that would work, just not sure its needed. We are not waiting for anything to finish. When the SR.scan returns, all SR.scans currently requested / in progress will have completed.'}, {'account_id': 6735, 'date': '2013-09-17 16:08:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I thought we were asserting that we don't have duplicate SR scans because they are blocked in XAPI - therefore it must be one SR operation running at the same time as another, in which case we can't rely on XAPI's blocking to fix it and multiple retries would make sense - if we know that these errors are down to racing."}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2013-09-19 08:47:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Bob No, I have no evidence for multiple SR scans (in xapi at once).

I am looking at multiple SR requests being collapsed into a single SR scan, that then reports a failure to all its callers.

The proper fix is to make XenAPI SR scans more robust, and to add a "Force SR Scan" that ensures the requests SR scan happens _after_ any previous scans have completed.

However, this bug is affecting users of OpenStack today, so I am trying to the simplest fix to mitigate the issues, while we wait for a fix from XenServer that addresses this.

Now, concern is to stop this chain of events:
* nova-compute request SR scan in periodic task
* nova-compute does modification to underlying SR
* nova-compute requests SR scan
* xapi collapses SR scan requests to both wait of a single SR scan process to finish
* SR scan fails because it got confused by the SR getting modified underneath its feet

Today:
* user sees operation failure, admin sees SR scan failure as cause

My plan:
* the above two SR requests are seperated out, so the second SR request for nova-compute only gets sent to xapi after the first has completed
* should any SR scan fail, we give it a single retry, which will kick off a new SR.scan, the previous one has now reported to be finished

An alternative case:
* xapi kicks of an SR scan in the background
* nova changes SR in a bad way
* nova requests SR scan
* SR scan fails, and reports failure
* we retry that SR scan, after the destructive change

I am happy to add retries, and sleeps, but it just doesn't seem to be needed, because the failures are so rare, and we know the previous SR scan has completed when we request the retry. I don't want to start adding big delays in reporting real failures in the hope of avoid this edge case race.'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2013-09-19 08:58:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Work In Progress

Need to add some retry logic, and approrpirate barage of tests that will need, and see if that seems more acceptable'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2013-09-26 13:46:56.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2013-09-26 13:47:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
xenapi: reduce impact of errors during SR.scan

There are some race conditions in SR.scan leading to errors similar to:
* The SR scan failed [opterr=['MAP_DUPLICATE_KEY', 'VDI', 'sm_config',
  '$UUID', 'vhd-blocks']]
* The SR scan failed [opterr=['UUID_INVALID', 'VDI', '$UUID']]

This seems to be happening because an SR.scan is happening when a xenapi
plugin is modifying the SR at the same time.

To reduce the likely-hood of this error, I have added a mutex around
calls to SR.scan to ensure nova-compute never makes more than one call
at once, because XenServer will join any extra SR.scan requests to
listen to the result of any current SR.scan that may be running.

In addition, when and error occurs during an SR scan, I have added a
retry loop, to attempt to stop these races from impacting users.

Fixes bug 1221293
Change-Id: Ib83e6e0f4f7fab2058fe137e32934606c4fe8f7e

[{'created': '2013-09-27 09:17:48.000000000', 'message': 'Set path_info in sub_slo manifest GET requests

The new_req Request object created for fetching
nested sub_slo manifests does not have its
path_info set to the sub_slo path before being
passed to GETorHEAD_base.

The sub manifest GET works fine because
GETorHEAD_base uses its path argument
(not req.path) to set up its connection,
BUT if an exception is thrown,
GETorHEAD_base uses req.path to construct
the log message - so the exception log would
have the wrong path.

Fixes bug 1231872

Change-Id: I0f0f969958f814d8a7053440d9de4e50796169e4
'}]
commit_message:
Set path_info in sub_slo manifest GET requests

The new_req Request object created for fetching
nested sub_slo manifests does not have its
path_info set to the sub_slo path before being
passed to GETorHEAD_base.

The sub manifest GET works fine because
GETorHEAD_base uses its path argument
(not req.path) to set up its connection,
BUT if an exception is thrown,
GETorHEAD_base uses req.path to construct
the log message - so the exception log would
have the wrong path.

Fixes bug 1231872

Change-Id: I0f0f969958f814d8a7053440d9de4e50796169e4

In the future we should completley deprecated the "image_name"
property on our Server class, but for now we can at least avoid
making N calls to glance per server in places where we know
it is most costly, such as the Instance overview page.

Fixes bug #1229128

Change-Id: Ib8dfb090db5a5db719042291f2f8a08c3e62b5e0
'}]
commit_message:
Limit the odds of making N calls to Glance for image names

In the future we should completley deprecated the "image_name"
property on our Server class, but for now we can at least avoid
making N calls to glance per server in places where we know
it is most costly, such as the Instance overview page.

Fixes bug #1229128

Change-Id: Ib8dfb090db5a5db719042291f2f8a08c3e62b5e0

commit_message:
Optimization of ceilometer API

- optimizing requests for resource by multithreading on resource level
  (each resource is obtaining stats in separate thread)
- fix last comment addressed in review
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/35589/
- fixing typos and misleading comments

Fixes bug 1218407
Change-Id: I24826bac7679bd075792691e3ed9a342aa1659fb

commit_message:
Sync Babel requirements with OpenStack/requirements

Sync requirements with Babel and WebTest version bump (amongst
other small changes from OpenStack Requirements). Babel version bump is
needed for tl_PH locale. WebTest raise fixes a gating issue with
Keystone.

Change-Id: I356d949d29168fd886b572fce869639a5f028735
Related-Bug: #1233694

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-23 21:02:12.000000000', 'message': "Extract hash_path and normalize_timestamp from ondisk

Move normalize_timestamp back to utils so code that talks to backend services
directly doesn't need to change it's import path.  The format of the
X-Timestamp header is part of the backend REST API and communicates intent
from the proxy server to the backend servers.  The storage layer may choose to
represent the sequence of backend writes in it's own format as long as it
honors the intent communicated by the proxy.

Move hash_path into ring.utils and move config parsing into config validation.
The format of the hash_path algorithm is primarily used by the proxy to
determine the partition of the resource named in the url of the request.  Once
it selects the partition there is not currently any additional validation
performed by the backend services.  The storage layer may choose to represent
the resource named in the url with it's own schema as long as it can guarantee
consistency with it's peers in the system.

By limiting the scope of the ondisk module we should be able to eventually
enforce the constraint that only the storage plugin layer and the default
storage background processes should touch code which has intimate knowledge of
the ondisk layout.  I think modules like direct_client, and the ring itself,
should certainly not have to import from ondisk.  Conversely these methods are
part of the bridge between front-end and back-end services and MUCH care
should taken to prevent incompatible changes between versions of swift,
specifically - we shouldn't move their import part lightly; but if we do move
it - lets make sure we find a long term home we can live with.

Change-Id: Ie7535069b07a1438d3545cbe6da28d683122a6c1

commit_message:
Extract hash_path and normalize_timestamp from ondisk

Move normalize_timestamp back to utils so code that talks to backend services
directly doesn't need to change it's import path.  The format of the
X-Timestamp header is part of the backend REST API and communicates intent
from the proxy server to the backend servers.  The storage layer may choose to
represent the sequence of backend writes in it's own format as long as it
honors the intent communicated by the proxy.

Move hash_path into ring.utils and move config parsing into config validation.
The format of the hash_path algorithm is primarily used by the proxy to
determine the partition of the resource named in the url of the request.  Once
it selects the partition there is not currently any additional validation
performed by the backend services.  The storage layer may choose to represent
the resource named in the url with it's own schema as long as it can guarantee
consistency with it's peers in the system.

By limiting the scope of the ondisk module we should be able to eventually
enforce the constraint that only the storage plugin layer and the default
storage background processes should touch code which has intimate knowledge of
the ondisk layout.  I think modules like direct_client, and the ring itself,
should certainly not have to import from ondisk.  Conversely these methods are
part of the bridge between front-end and back-end services and MUCH care
should taken to prevent incompatible changes between versions of swift,
specifically - we shouldn't move their import part lightly; but if we do move
it - lets make sure we find a long term home we can live with.

Change-Id: Ie7535069b07a1438d3545cbe6da28d683122a6c1

commit_message:
Add pylru for an LRU decorator

Python3 has LRU decorator in functools, but Python 2 does not.
pylru offers an LRU decorator in Python 2, and shows noticeable
performance improvement.

** Needed by the openstack-marconi project.

Change-Id: Id161eeaffc8e0ab5f9bdd7bc3fefdc9a6c042979

'}, {'account_id': 6484, 'date': '2013-09-11 04:59:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 6549, 'date': '2013-09-17 08:16:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 6549, 'date': '2013-09-19 20:34:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: No score

Seems jbresnah and flaper87 has different thought. Let's see what others think."}, {'account_id': 6493, 'date': '2013-09-19 21:38:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

This looks good but I have 1 concern.  As it stands right now we trap an error, add a user friendly message to it, and then re-raise a new exception.  The bug is that the new exceptions are HTTP and not appropriate for the notifier.  By just logging and raising it does solve that bug, however we lose some information.  The exception now does not contain the msg string that was constructed.  It is not clear to me that when the error is trapped higher up in the stack that as friendly of an error message can be created.  For most of the exceptions this is not a problem, my concern lies with ValueError and Exception.  Up the stack will we be able to construct as friendly of messages for the user or will we not know exactly why the exception occurred.

We could solve this by creating a new exception in those cases with the msg (however this has the disadvantage of losing stack information).

I am ok with approving this as is but I want to have this discussion first."}, {'account_id': 6484, 'date': '2013-09-21 05:27:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

It's a good discussion. IMHO, current implement is reasonable. Because except the ValueError and Exception, most of the other exceptions are *expected*, so we can show a friendly message to end user. But for ValueError and the generic Exception, it's better to let the end user know what's the root cause, I mean the exception trace. Since we don't know what happened."}, {'account_id': 616, 'date': '2013-09-24 17:56:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I've bumped this from rc1 to icehouse.

I really want to ensure that the notifier is not taking on HTTP formatting  responsibilities. In principle, the notifier doesn't have any more information about the meaning of exceptions raised during set_data() than does the ultimate user of the domain-image interface. So the concern, while valid, doesn't seem to be first order here.

However, I think this patch is a little sloppy. What I should be doing is taking the existing HTTP error formatting behavior and putting it all entirely in the image_data controller. On closer review, its clear to me that this patch doesn't do that. For one, there are some little differences in some of the http messages. Secondly, the image_data controller has some slightly more complex handling of NotFound errors that needs to be maintained (and possibly clarified).

Since this isn't a big risk for backports, let's hold off a bit until after RC1 goes out."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-10-02 06:03:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-10-02 06:03:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}]

commit_message:
Do not load driver if not defined

In the ResourceManager do not try to load a driver if it's not passed
by parameter or defined in db. This is causing DriverNotFound exception
to be raised when you try to update a node where driver is None.

Change-Id: Ie8fc9b25d4d7ba7045b4820f8e273bc76cd992cd

commit_message:
Update from requirements

The specifically desired change is the one to setup.py which removes the
reference to d2to1. d2to1 is very undesirable to consume due to its
explicit dependency on distribute that is still unfixed. While we're
doing it, go ahead and do the full update.py from requirements.txt to
reduce later churn.

Change-Id: Ia862337b904ba021db8fc21cb21b886f948bd3fc

So this means the server dictates the language, rather than given full control to the client. The implementation of this patch looks fine, but I'm not sure of the implications TBH. Is it not better to have better determinism in APIs?"}, {'account_id': 5371, 'date': '2013-09-05 15:57:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@p-draigbrady, that was my original assumption when working on the API localization support. Originally, the messages would come back as the system locale when there was no support for translation, and I switched it to default to en_US.

When I had the bug opened up against me, I argued that by design I switched the default, but the point was made that by using the system locale, the default can be configured by the system.

Regardless of the default, the Accept-Language header always takes precedence if it exists in the request.'}, {'account_id': 1812, 'date': '2013-09-18 17:33:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Matthew I agree with your original idea for deterministic APIS. I.E. en_US unless otherwise specified by the client.
So I'm against this change, though I notice that it's gone
into all other projects :("}, {'account_id': 7996, 'date': '2013-09-19 14:22:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

Given the current implementation the client always dictates the locale using the Accept-Language HTTP header.

The change is just to make OpenStack comply with common practices where the default locale comes from the system, instead of it being hard coded.'}, {'account_id': 8574, 'date': '2013-09-22 02:45:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

Support to remove the hard coded 'en_US'."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-09-29 06:03:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 5371, 'date': '2013-09-30 14:31:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Restored'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-09-30 14:35:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

commit_message:
Use system locale for default request language

Remove en_US as the default language when no header is provided, and use
None instead. Upon translation None will be defaulted to system locale
as it was before API translation changes.

fixes bug 1214476

Change-Id: Ic33c94c29993ceb944d7c22d2e754cb938db7503

The heat slow test NeutronResourcesTestJSON is causing problems
for the other heat tests when run concurrenty.

Because NeutronResourcesTestJSON creates a network and the other tests
do not specify any, an amibiguity is created. This means that nova
server creation fails due to not knowing which network to attach to.

This change explicity launches servers with the network specified in
config compute.fixed_network_name.

This may mean that these tests cannot be run with nova networking.

to gate heat-slow tests on nova networking.

commit_message:
Explicity specify network for heat slow tests

The heat slow test NeutronResourcesTestJSON is causing problems
for the other heat tests when run concurrenty.

Because NeutronResourcesTestJSON creates a network and the other tests
do not specify any, an amibiguity is created. This means that nova
server creation fails due to not knowing which network to attach to.

This change explicity launches servers with the network specified in
config compute.fixed_network_name.

This may mean that these tests cannot be run with nova networking.
This is most likely not a problem as there are currently no plans
to gate heat-slow tests on nova networking.

Change-Id: I16d50271a36c9bc9d0c4fb0588ae75ba100b145f

commit_message:
Update tox config

An updated tox config is needed to deal with accidental installs of
pre-release software we don't want. Additionally, this update should
make running tox tests quicker due to skipping the sdist.

Closes-Bug: 1233357
Change-Id: I814850d7e108a3502297bbbdda506e260d2a86cb

commit_message:
Revert "unskipping bug related to test_stamp_pattern.py"

This reverts commit 60100a3eaec620a8b9946b3378caed6c23122310.

Given the current state of non-deterministic failures in the gate
right now bringing this test back for debugging the failure is just
adding fuel to the fire. We should wait for things to stabilize
again before removing the skip.

Change-Id: Iff5fb31074ddf7dc0e9320ac19ac71fa451a8820

commit_message:
Remove unused LOG

In some files, we import logging and define
LOG, but we never used it later, so i remove
those unused LOG and make horizon code clean.

Fixed: bug #1231761
